deck_excerpt: Semi-competitive Generaider deck with some twists to make it more viable.
deck_description:
This deck uses the basic Generaider engine plus some out of engine support to turn it from a slow, stall deck into a massive perpetual motion machine. This deck can out-grind the likes of Runick Spright, Floo, and Dark World. Even the worst hands can give you a solid board, with okay hands giving an OTK.

The core idea is to get out as many lv9's as possible to pull cards from the extra deck. With the entire extra's theme being large removals leaving your opponent open to huge OTK's. Using Vala, Mardel, Loptr, Boss Stage, WLM and DWD to push out anywhere from 1 to 5 lv9's on any given turn; with a lot of play from the hand and GY.

deck_excerpt: Not a deck profile, but I can't upload articles for Trinity so this will have to suffice. Reupload in articles at your behest.
deck_description:
This article is pretty long overdue and may be a bit dated when it comes to assessing just how inane some of the effects and engines are in the modern state of the game, but in the event that they aren't so hilariously unbalanced to the point where decks are homogenous piles of the same cards, then this piece will at least retain some merit. If not, then let it serve as a snapshot in surveying and reflecting on one of the fundamental aspects of deckbuilding with a more measured outlook for this alternative format's previous eras.

Full disclosure: Since I can't upload articles directly to this site, this is going up as a deck profile with the article attached. Anyone who has the capability of uploading articles for Trinity feel free to canabalize this piece and reupload at your leisure. I will unlist this in the event that transpires. Just remember to give credit. ^^

Trinity Format's take on being a psuedo-Highlander format invites a lot of creativity when it comes to deckbuilding concepts that can be borrowed from other highlander formats but explored much more heavily in its own right. For example: being able to run additional copies of the same impactful card or intentionally increasing the deck size not because it's optimal but because it's required for the deck's composition to be legal are just some of the ways to recognize a Trinity deck from its other Highlander counterparts.

Looking at these capabilities, one might think it's best to simply jam in as many pointed cards and duplicates as they see fit until the deck is completely bloated and you reach the 60 card maximum for decks in the format; however, this isn't always best (and in-fact, shouldn't necessarily be the go-to option, even though it often winds up topping in the end--- though I do suspect that such a reality largely is the consequence of the game having an abundence of powerful silver bullets and low-effort engines that can steal games rather it being attributed to statistical foresight.

We'll go over each of the categories of compositions to paint a better picture of the probability and benefits associated with each size. I'll do my best to make things digestible and not bore you with numbers if you aren't a super numbers-oriented individual. For a quick-reference to everything ahead of time, here's a table that's provided in the official server that highlights the odds associated with a single card being the focal point in any given scenario.

Deck Size  | % Chance opening Trinity | % Increase | % Chance not opening Trinity | % Decrease

30               | 16.7%                                   | 16.7%         | 16.7%                                          | 16.7%
35               | 26.8%                                   | 10.1%         | 14.3%                                          |   2.4%
40               | 33.8%                                   |     7%          | 12.5%                                          |   1.8%
45               | 38.6%                                   |  4.8%          | 11.1%                                          |    1.4%
50               | 42.3%                                   |  3.7%          |    10%                                          |    1.1%
55               | 45.1%                                   |  2.8%          |   9.1%                                          |    0.9%
60               | 47.4%                                   |  2.3%          |   8.3%                                          |    0.8%

The Benefits of Smaller Compositions
30-40

If your strategy would benefit from seeing specific combinations of cards and lacks any real Garnets or has insanely high OTK/FTK potential, then this is the number range to generally shoot for. While 30 seems really appealing for seeing the most consistent combinations of specific cards in hand, handtraps, or side deck bombs, it's generally not considered to be optimal unless your strategy benefits specifically from having as little cards as possible within it. The reason for this stems strictly from the fact that the Pointed Card list exists and in such list, there exists cards like Pot of Greed, Extravegence, and Prosperity that can actively  help hand-fix and also serve as a means of getting additional power cards that would otherwise be a boon for the deck as a whole. If such cards weren't on the list or the disparity between having pointed card bombs (or even just another duplicate) wasn't so noticeable, then 30 would be considered ideal in a lot of cases. Since it isn't, 35 is considered to be the smallest deck size that is both compotent and competitive to run with and honestly a lot better than people give it credit for.

Strategies that fall under this category are decks like Thunder Dragon, Gem-Knight, and OTK Pendulum where combination of specific cards (or types of cards) is generally more valuable than seeing individually swingy and powerful cards!

40's a pretty decent middle ground; however, you are only afforded 2 points with it so it's only really great when it comes to strategies that are consistent enough out of the gate and just need additional copies of their primary playstarter. Strategies like Lunalight, Tenyi, and Ancient Warriors fit in this category. Due to this boon and existence of the Pointed List; however, it is pretty easy to lean further into the next composition...

The Golden Ratio (In my Opinion)
45

Funnily enough this number affords us 3 Trinities while also only being 5 cards over the standard TCG deck minimum. This allows us to see any one single playstarter (at 3 copies in total) nearly 40% of the time, ignoring the hyper consistency of a good chunk of strategies in finding said starter without the need of duplicates like Orcust, Cyber Dragon, and Myutant. Taking those things into consideration, you'll find said starter much more often in your opening hands to the point where you'd be capable of stuffing the deck with more techs, answers, disruptions, and handtraps because of the consistency being in your favor. Addtionally, in matches, you'll find that while you won't be able to see the side deck nearly as often as a 30-40 list, you'll still see it more often than our 50+ (and especially our 60) opponents which comes up more often than one might think as Games 2-3 when prepared for correctly tend to be longer than Game 1 which usually favors the person who simply drew better.

In the event that you're not capping out on maximizing the copies of a card, that's still ideal in the case of 45 as even with just running 1 extra duplicate, you're still increasing your odds of opening said playstarter on top of being able to pull cards from the Pointed List and see said cards from that list more often than the bloated 50+ card decks would be able to, especially in margins that are more noticeable in tournament settings.

These reasons are why I always recommend shooting for 45 to start out when deckbuilding and judging if you need to go higher or cut lower. You do give up a lot of consistency for decks that feature more Garnets with their engines; however, if you're on strategies that demand duplicates, certain power cards, or running Garnets (but never wanting to draw them) then the next composition is ideal.

The Benefits of Larger Compositions
50-55

If you've browsed the Tournament topping list, it isn't too uncommon to see a lot of decks falling under this category (or just being 60 cards in general). This is usually because of banlist oversights and certain cards being valued way lower than they should be and being included for generously free wins in bracket or simply because a pilot's comfortable with navigating more cursed hands because they'd rather elect to running specific power cards and having the chance of drawing them, even if they may be lower than most or rarely seen during their Swiss matches. Assessments of such ideas aside, the premise of the larger composition is simple: abusing the point system without reducing hand quality to utter rubbish (sometimes)!

At this size, hands are exceeding random in nature barring the occasional appearance of the one playstarter or duplicate that is largely responsible for the 50-55 angle in the first place. Fundamentally, this would give strategies like this an Achilles' Heel to aim for; however, modern deck building intrinsically builds around this issue by way of exploring engines and powerful filler cards that can often win games as an unintended back-up option rather than the focal point. Piloting a larger pile without much conhesion or familiarity with the deck is often a daunting task and not recommended for newer players or people trying out cards they've never even read nor touched before simply because the hands just won't be the same or close to the same each time. You will have to deal with an oversaturation of handtraps or answers sometimes and you will be forced to sometimes play an OTK deck like a midrange deck until you're able to find the correct pieces over the course of the duel. If you're interested in going down this route but still prefer consistency above all else, I strongly recommend playing strategies that feature numerous ways of accessing premium cards, such as Dragon decks, HERO, and the upper echelon of the more complex Zombie and Plant decks. If you've got Garnets galore but combos a-plenty, then this is the range to shoot for most of the time.

Now all that leaves is... oh, Holactie--- no!

The Consequences of the Pile
60

For being the absolute maximum deck size and attributing someone the point cap of six points (which is honestly more impactful than one might think), the returns often aren't worth it for players not jamming loads of engines, duplicates, nor cards that do well in interacting with one another regardless of what's in the opening hand. The reason I consider this composition to be a trap is mostly because of two really important things to consider:

1) Hand Quality

Hands are entirely random and do not often feature the same openers barring some obvious outliers with strategies that feature support so consistent you would find said openers in 180 card decks. Given that this is still highlander at it's core, you would find so many hands that feature your singles more than your duplicates, so the importance and worth of the individual is put on display here more than anything. Combinations of cards still have relevance in some capacity, but again, barring the aforementioned circumstances of the 180 card deck, you really should be expecting to look at each hand between games and gauge how to navigate things like a puzzle until you find what you need to close the game out. If you find that individual card with its near 48% chance of being attained in your opening hand, then you should likely consider ways of playing around it further to help convert that high probability into a consistent turnover of a victory. This is usually done with less consistent decks by way of running more staples and disruption as the space needed to fill in the blank spots to add up to 60 (and still be expected to draw disruptions on a regular basis) is often pretty flexible.

2) Side Decking

This issue is pretty related to the first in that it's mostly considered with regards to opening hands and draws-over-time; however, due to this being the absolute maximum that one can take into a tournament setting, you must understand that anyone (including your opponent) on this count should not be realistically favored to see their main deck side board in any capacity unless they're slotting in several cards that feature similar effects. While technically bad practice, it's honestly fine to disrespect the sideboards from these players during the opening turns if the consequences wouldn't be so dire as to end the game immediately; however, if you're the pilot of said strategy on a 60 card composition then I strongly recommend siding Extra Deck answers and cards instead. The reason for this primarily is done to treat the Extra Deck like a second hand that you can access (usually) without much issue nor demand and due to the insane effects on some monsters, you can probably steal games as well! For example, being able to side in cards like Crimson Blader or Abyss Dweller would be much more effective and accessible for decks that can summon said cards instead of middling with their already-suffering hand quality and risking dead-er draws in the main deck with similar tech choices. If your strategy can't afford the Extra Deck spaces or simply cannot make them; then your next best option is to side in engines that get the job done effectively. The most prominent of these that can honestly be overbearing or too swingy at times being Timelords, with Zaphion, Maiden, and Kamion often being sided in decks that run Foolish Burial or Level 1 support to utilize Maiden effectively, thus increasing the odds of seeing her substantially over just any 1 individual side board card.

-

 Now, if you're curious as to which decks I personally think don't mind being at the 60 card count, I honestly can't say for certain. Decks that benefit from taking advantage of Unbound cards can find value here since they improve hand quality; however, those decks also benefit from smaller deck sizes as well. If a deck is running so many Garnets that 60 is considered optimal solely for that purpose, then the deck likely can be reassessed and edited to be smaller and more consistent with less or the same number of Garnets. 60 honestly is a composition for those who either can't be bothered to cut cards or would rather see what would happen if you were capable of combining several engines in Highlander and seeing how they would interact with one another over the course of a game or match. Barring those examples, it is probably optimal and worth considering the 60 composition with strategies that are hyper consistent, blatantly broken, and/or features a fount of bombs that can win the duel regardless of whatever else exists in your hand at the time. While Trinity likely isn't designed to cater to that last example's PoV (as it wouldn't really be that interesting to observe from a spectator's side of things) and often times the strategies that abuse these qualities are often struck by the community banlist either immediately or overtime anyway.

Veterans and champions of the format alike have proven that the 60 card composition can and does work throughout the many years that this format has existed, so take my criticisms more so as a means of insight rather than solely as a metric to keep you away from experimenting with said card count; however, if you're finding yourself bricking with your build then consider sacrificing that extra point or two and reducing the cards in the main deck to a composition that better caters to your desired playstyle!

Hopefully this article was insightful. My word isn't at all absolute and half of the explanations do come from a place of opinions; however, this conversation often isn't had when it comes to introducing newer players to the game and it's a shame because it's one of the cooler parts to consider when taking advantage of what makes Trinity different. I hope that you (regardless of your own experience) take away something from this read that you can experiment with in the Format or use as an advantage against opponents belonging to a specific composition bracket.

 

Thanks for reading!

deck_excerpt: Wanna rule the Battle Phase without being anime about it? Well discard those maidens and embrace the beast inside with GBs!
deck_description:
Orange you glad this isn't an anime girl deck? No? Well, I tried. In any event unlike Dragonmaids who can definitely outspeed and likely outvalue them, Gladiator Beasts maintain their rule over the Battle Phase in a pretty substantial way with really potent fusions that tend to outright end games on the spot once resolving! Unlike past iterations of this deck, we'll be focusing primarily on the value offered from a pure build rather than seeking assisstance from engines like Amazement and Swordsoul who have just become unfortunately a bit too slow with regards to the modern game and how it's played. So, bolster those defenses and train your eyes to perceive the weaknesses in your opponent's front line because it's time to enter the colosseum again!


- Difficulty -

While Glads have historically been either in the far end of control or combo, this build aims to be primarily midrange and close games out sometime after the openers have been established and dealt with. Due to this, you'll be forced to deal with and answer your opponent 90% of the time, respecting backrow, destruction effects, and taking measure of your assets before deciding what and when to commit. It's less stressful than it sounds but a single mistake can outright cost you the duel due to the main deck card quality of GBs being so much lower than modern cards!

 - Consistency -
/
Depends exactly on what you're expecting really. You can and should be expected to find one Gladiator Beast (who can actually tag out) in addition to a backrow that can back them up in each opener; however, the worth of those two items together may not be enough to actually be your opening play within a duel. When it is, you're off to the races as any one of the GBs who can tag are functionally all starters within the deck. That said; however, your combo-ing off potential should be reserved for when you know your opponent can't retaliate, as the contact fusion method with GBs leaves you with literally nothing once they shuffle themselves back into the deck. If your aim is to just summon a GB and slam-a-jam backrow until you win then this is a hyper consistent list for you- though you'd probably want more backrow than I've provided here. If your aim is to combo and pop/negate things left and right, then I've got some bad news for you and you may want to explore a Melffy/Tri-Brigade/Andal build!

- Sackiness -

Between the Fusions' insane effects, Morganite, and the many combat tricks including the hand effects from monsters, you'll generally be representing a threat or counterattack at any stage of the game; however, the ability to actually win a topdeck war (especially if there's a monster on the field) is pretty lacking and leaves much to be desired. Should you find yourself exhausted of resources your only real out is Gladiator Beast United with the appropriate materials in the GY.

- Viability -

Midrange and tempo strategies tend to be generally favored when it comes to taking victories simply due to the effect that slowing the opponent down and out-grinding them in resources can have in Trinity. If you're able to stun enough pieces and break apart their board, then Gladiator Beasts can win a lot of matchups, especially with the removal provided here with the backrow lineup. It's worth noting however that this same thing can be achieved with any other midrange deck, the difficulty from GBs just comes from every main deck one being functionally a Garnet until they resolve their respective effects.


Pros:

  • Safety Nets: The sheer amount of disruption and answer cards we're running in this list make it so that our plays are usually insulated in some way. We should never, ever really be in any remote danger during a game as long as we have a Gladiator Beast and a backline to back them up. Looping Gladiator Beast Charge can also be almost as devastating as looping War Chariot in a lot of cases as well.

  • Noteworthy Protection: Barring generics and our focus on clearing as many pesky pieces of backrow as possible with this build, thanks to Rejection, our Gladiator Beasts are protected from most things until it's time to commit to the Battle Phase. It also doubles their usual output from a battle and quickly turns 1 into 2 which is usually fusion play.

  • No Andal!: Rescue Rabbit openers and lines are great for getting into Panther or Dragases or setting up a three material fusion but boy did it suck drawing into that card and not having it be able to tag out like the others. Well, there's none of that anymore. We've compromised the Andal combos and random chance of drawing into Rescue Rabbit before it in the interest of having more playable hands overall. Just protect your guy(s) and run over the opponents. There's no need for any fancy business.

  • Potent Wincons: Thanks to Tamer Editor and Secutor, accessing Domitianus and Heraklinos is pretty straightforward, even in Trinity. You just won't be doing it turn 1 like you would in the TCG. We'll also be stealing some wins with cheeky pops using Gladiator Beast United to either represent an additional attack or a Gyzarus when appropriate! Heck, maybe more because this Miracle Fusion is insane.

 

Cons:

  • They're all Garnets: All of them. Opening a Gladiator Beast will probably have you saying "man, I wish this one stayed in the deck or was another Gladiator Beast." That's basically this deck's entire experience and why we're only playing the ones that matter. Sadly, that little dilemma will always remain in this deck and there isn't much to be done about it outside of Contact Fusing or bringing out Augustus. It feels even worse that a Trinity is being spent on Proving Ground just to increase the odds of finding a Glad, especially in a pinch. Pick a Glad and pray.

  • Extra Deck: The Extra Deck will usually be useless sometimes if you find yourself in a situation where you need to break down a board before you start committing to anything flashy. It's for this reason that we're not on any Extra Deck Trinities here and I'd personally advise against it. Fortunately, this does also mean that we're pretty insulated against cards like Titanocider which is pretty popular this format.

  • Forehead Girl is an FTK: Ash solos. Godspeed

  • Conflicting Trumps: Despite the lower handtrap count here, Noxious, Vespasius and Hedge Guard can and will be restricted by Morganite after it is activated. Usually you'll be resolving the necessary GBs you want prior but since finding Morganite is random, you'll need to make judgment calls about when to activate it to take advantage of its payoffs.


Now with that out of the way, let's get into some of the demo setups you'll be wanting to aim for.

 


OPENERS

This list isn't about finding gas, it's about opening defenses and protecting your Gladiator. You'll ideally be wanting to always go first. If you're going with no backup, I'd strongly encourage just combat tricking out the opponent. There isn't any specific opener you'll want to look for since Gladiator Beasts take on a midrange playstyle here (without Andal anyway), so your opening hands determine your line of play. Here's a few pointers though if you're inexperienced with them:

  • Phalanx: Control a Gladiator Beast and protect them with backrow. If there's something you can use to either change a monster's battle position to make them vulnerable on your turn or modify combat stats so your monster will survive the attack, that's ideal.

  • Ob-Noxious: If you've opened Noxious and backrow, feel free to set those cards and outright pass. Usually people will just attack you outright, so you punish with Noxious. Bin either something you want to bring back with Darius (who Noxious will tag out into after) or bin something you don't want to draw, like Augustus. Tag as appropriate.


The openers aren't always ideal and will vary from game-to-game, especially post-siding. The main thing to do is plan ahead. Measure your options and weigh your forms of interaction well. Everything in your deck is an extremely limited resource and this deck lacks card draw.


MIDGAME

This is where Gladiator Beasts shine really. The main thing to note is that the monsters summoned via Gladiator Rejection aren't treated as being summoned by a Gladiator Beast Monster, so all of the GB effects shouldn't be active. You'll be doing your best Unchained-meets-Dragonmaid impression here... despite preceding both of those archetypes. Hmm.

  • Bestiari: Your Spell/Trap removal. This card's also really important for making Gyzarus who is your Icarus Attack on-summon. S/T hate's pretty restricted across the board in Trinity format and most decks only rely on generics to get it done. Since Glad Beasts tag out often, you have this form of removal going for you on top of the generic removal you're already running here. It's worth noting that this card's effect to destroy is mandatory, so don't summon it willy-nilly otherwise you might end up having to pop your own backline.

  • Murmillo: Your Monster removal. This card's your go-to for checking the board and clearing potential threats. Its combat stats leave much to be desired, but it doesn't have to partake in combat if it's already won now has it? Use it for fusion material when you can, or take an open attack. Don't get greedy with the fish.

  • The Tag Team: Gladiator Beast War Chariot's an amazing Counter Trap and since most win conditions in Trinity format revolve around Monster effects, having access to this is nothing to scoff at. Samnite grabs this for you and Equeste loops this for you. Loop these two as necessary to keep up the War Chariot pressure and you'll have your opponent on the ropes.

  • Chain Destruction: Magnum the Reliever enables some fun combinations akin to that of Cyber Slash Harpie Lady; however, we can also use it as a means of getting our fusions that can be Resurrected into the GY- like Gyzarus. We'll be primarily taking advantage of Magnum's effects solely through Fusion Deployment as the other methods are too slow to consider.

  • Sagittari Cycling: Thanks to all of them being functional Garnets in the hand outside of for Augustus and Vespasius, it means that you can pitch them without second thought to Sagittari and dig for much better and reliable cards in the form of your Spells and Traps. Combined with Besitari, Gyzarus, and Equeste, Sagitarri also helps for being another Icarus target to blow away the opponent.

Games should usually resolve themselves by midgame due to all of the removal, but Gladiator Beasts can definitely go into a late or grind game.


LATEGAME & CLOSERS

The killing blow. Leave absolutely no room for a comeback. This is the Gladiator's Proving Ground.

  • Secutor: Resolving Secutor once basically wins the game on the spot. Resolving it during the opponent's turn? Well, that's probably traumatizing to say the least. Ideally you'll be wanting to bring out those that are all-stars in the midgame (as listed above); however, if you're ready to go in for the kill, summon out Laquari or Vespasius instead for fusion setups we'll cover just below.

  • Tamer Editor: This thing just cheats. Summon it with Rejection lines or by using Attorix on your own turn.

  • Domitianus: Monster effect activation negation with no cost whatsoever and dictates who attacks who during your opponent's turn? Make this when you know it's a valid win condition. Just keep in mind that it only tags out into only 1 other Gladiator Beast. This card is really bad to use mid game as a result since, if it would fall, you would be put severely behind for the contact fusion play. Don't be greedy with Domitianus.

  • Heraklinos: Your Spell/Trap activation negation station. This card ain't even once per turn. As long as you have cards to discard, you can keep up the suffocation against your opponent. Unfortunately, this card doesn't have a tag out nor a float, so it should be used exclusively as a finisher where you're confident it will win. If it happens to get removed, you'll be set back pretty far.

 


The most important thing to note about this list is that any and all Spell/Traps selected here can and should be experimented with and swapped out to fit your playstyle with the deck in a given format. This is not a one size fits all situation and due to the variance concerning the hands, the learning curve with deciphering the best way to spend one's opening turns is definitely pretty steep. Regardless, here's a handful of ideas just to throw your way should you aim to adjust this baseline into something more focused elsewhere:

Viability Boosters: Melffy/Andal Engine | Amazement | SPYRAL | Rescue-ACE | Gate Guardian Engine

General Purpose: Geartown, Loop of Destruction, Archfiend's Staff of Despair, Gladiator Beast's Battle Manica, Burden of the Mighty, Dinosaur Shenanigans, The Golden Swordsoul

Thanks for reading, and I hope this has convinced you to give the deck a try! I actually have taken a similar build like this into bracket and it performed decently well in its games; though, the matches where I couldn't find a single piece of interaction really did show off just how slow the monsters can be when not backed up by the necessary defensive line. All-in-all, it's always refreshing to see Gladiator Beasts doing well in some capacity, especially against the nonsensical card quality that the game continues to offer at its forefront.

45 Card Deck = 3 Points with 3p used.
1p Gladiator Rejection (Extra Copy)
1p Gladiator Beast United (Extra Copy)
.5p Solemn Judgment
.5p Time-Tearing Morganite

Hopefully this helps with the Gladiator Beast's Comeback. See you in the arena.

deck_excerpt: deck is polished over a ton of gruuling hours to make sure you all have a list
Finally emerging from the submerged trench come the Fish from the black border, not at all associated with those Ghoti pale imitators.
deck_description:
A classic list that I finally feel a little more confident in recommending in some capacity thanks to the release of the Number support, Sakitama, and Shark updates. While still suffering from Xyz weaknesses inherent only to Trinity Format, the deck overall has received a number of indirect buffs that could honestly bring it back into the spotlight as a consideration for a R4nk deck.

- Difficulty -

Probably the easiest deck to play with very little in terms of being able to have back-up plays or anything for whenever you're disrupted. There's a few shenanigans with 7-Colored Fish and Squire, but barring those specific cards, you'll be primarily just limited to doing the same things every turn, but with different cards along the way. Which isn't a bad thing, simple is effective in Trinity.

 - Consistency -

Each hand should feature a way to opening an Xyz. As to whether or not you'll be locked into a WATER, Number, or specific one depends entirely on the components of said hand. Ideally, you'll be going for Hope anyway as it meets most of the criteria, recycles your materials, and threatens the board while bolstering any weaker links that you happen to build along the way.

- Sackiness -

Even with the 1 card Xyzs present in the deck, there isn't too much in the way of stealing games, just slightly faster than average plays. The deck overall is pretty honest to a fault. Adding more backrow and sacrificing some of the consistency would greatly improve the sackiness, turning those 1card plays into 1card walls.

- Viability -

The idea with this build is to establish a presence then keep building onto it. Very rarely does that happen in modern Trinity and in the event it actually does, you're probably winning to begin with as starting your turn with any non-detrimental monster helps close the game out much faster. The lack of Links and more interactive Spell/Traps makes this deck more selfish and self-contained than possible counterparts. To improve its viability, one might look to Ghoti for more interactive turn 1 plays.

Pros:

  • Easy Starts: Buzzsaw Shark or a combination of any two cards that summon themselves out gets you rolling. Your opening play should always consist of making a Rank 4 either disrupt or defend going first.

  • Loops: Wyvern, Graydle Dragon, Salvation, and Overlay Network offer a decent variety of methods to looping your important pieces and keeping value going.

  • 7 Colored Fish?: It's a Normal Monster- which helps with getting around the summon limit in a lot of instances! Due to this status, it's also synergistic with some alternative choices in deck building that we'll cover by the end.

Cons:

  • Rank 4 Chunkiness: If you fail to open Buzzsaw Shark (or it gets disrupted) or fail to find an extender in addition to a normal summon, you'll be behind by quite a bit. While this isn't a super common occurrence, it can set you back in a duel pretty far. Fortunately, the toolbox options in the Extra Deck help with comebacks.

  • Exosister Tax: While the Exosister engine is great and it's good to have it back in action, they aren't WATER monsters and Martha prevents going into anything besides an Exosister.

  • Prone to Disruption: Most decks will want to interact with you by your second summon, before the Xyz touches down. Sometimes they'll interact with you on the Xyz Summon itself. Either way, when this happens and you don't have follow-up in the form of an extender, it can be quite rough. It's one of the caveats of playing a pseudo-traditional Xyz strategy in a format with capped summons.

Now with that out of the way, let's get into some of the demo setups you'll be wanting to aim for.

OPENERS
The hand quality and/or number of extenders in the hand will always make the permuations of the gamestates more or less challenging to emulate; though, this much was obvious. That being said, in the 1st turns of the duel, you ideally just want to have a conga line of Xyzs rolling out. This can be enabled by the following:

  • Defensive Line - Having Hope: Leading with Number 37: Hope Woven Dragon Spider Shark isn't the worst thing you can do, especially if it's made using Buzzsaw Shark. Being able to threaten a 1k drop across the board on top of resurrecting your one card starter makes it exert some pressure while also doubling as a decent attacker. It shines best alongside others or backrow.

  • Exosister Avatar: With Mikalis back to Unlimited, Exosisters honestly should be featured more frequently in any Rank 4 strategy as their Xyz Monsters are great if you have the space. With Traptrix Rafflesia gone and this list not featuring Bagooska, if you're aiming to prevent a specific aspect of your opponent's gameplan, then turboing Mikailis is up your alley. Pick up the Exosister Arment and set it. During your opponent's turn you can either tag into Usophiel who prevents GY effects (and if she survives, is just a compulse) or Jibrine who is more of a supportive card to help you push for early lethal if your opponent's off to a slow start. If you happen to open Arment, simply make Jibrine instead and open up the option of tagging into Mikailis for her Quick Effect banish! Kaspitell's also great, but is more specific to certain match-ups.

As you can tell, the openers and lines can be pretty linear. Most of the advanced tactics comes from summon management using the non-Effect Monsters and choosing the right Xyz for the job. Rarely will your opponent be generous enough to give you a second or third chance at answering their board.

MIDGAME & CLOSERS
There's only a few real setups to aim for if you find yourself in the midgame grind or aim to end the game outright.

  • Drill Driver Vespenato: This card's basically another copy of Number 37; however, it's also a piercer! Its utility usually comes up whenever you unfortunately cannot find Whitefish Salvage nor Avarice.

  • Exosisters Magnifica: A bit of a pipe dream most of the time, but Exosisters can be just as sticky as the rest of your lineup or simply return to the fray thanks to Xyz Reborn, Revive Splash, or the simple ressurection spells in the deck. Both of its effects are extremely potent, so if you're able to go for it and your Exosister Xyzs are exhausted, I honestly encourage it!
  • Valiant Shark Lancer: This card when paired with Abyss Dweller or Number 37 can easily close out games pretty quickly. Unfortunately, due to its Rank being 5, the setups for it are mostly specific to Buzzsaw Shark, Lantern Shark, and Penguin Squire. However, if achieved successfully, you have now earned yourself a Quick-Effect monster pop. Usually an opponent should aim to take out your Dweller or Number 37 because it turns of Valiant from being a Quick-Effect and removes both forms of pressure at once. When this happens, you'll be able to stack your deck with any sacky option of your choice. I recommend White Mirror, Whitefish Salvage, Pot of Avarice, Instant Fusion, and Monster Reborn.

  • Graydle Dragon: This isn't super consistent to pull off but can be a bit easier through Ice Barrier to find Squire more often. When Graydle Dragon resolves in this deck, you should almost always be using it to clear two cards. Don't settle for just one, Tornado Dragon or Light Dragon @Ignister can do that instead. Graydle Dragon also being able to float is massive as well- although the monster will just be a generic material more than anything else.

Games should usually resolve themselves by midgame. The grind game in this deck isn't the best per se.

While simple in nature, the deck's playstyle favors decision-making and proper risk assessment for problem solving. There's no Numeron Dragon OTK for you to get out of situations easily. Things will have to take patience and proper identification of win conditions to achieve consistent victories with this deck. Here's a handful of ideas just to throw your way should you aim to adjust this baseline into something more focused elsewhere:

Viability Boosters: Tenyi | Dinosaur | Traptrix | Performage w/ Penguin Garden & Guard Penguin | Level 2 Ghoti Engine | Bagooska

General Purpose: Piercing the Darkness, Dogmatika, Super Team Buddy Force Unite!!, CXyzs and Barian Support, Icejade Engine

50 Card Deck = 4 Points with 4p used.
1p Buzzsaw Shark (Extra Copy)
1p Buzzsaw Shark (Extra Copy)
1p Abyss Shark (Extra Copy)
.5p Evilswarm Exciton Knight
.5p Instant Fusion

Now that the tides have finally started to turn in this strategy's favor, it's time for it to make a splash! Thanks for reading and see you next time~

deck_excerpt: Kashtira without the 2nd wave of support still packs a punch in Masterduel!
deck_description:
Kashtira without it's 2nd wave of support (Aristheart, Kashtira Theosis, Pressured Planet Wraitsoth etc.) may not be full power, but it still is a formidable deck in Masterduel ladder. Able to pack a million staples in the strategy and several supporting engines, Kashtira can still fight vs. Masterduel ladder heavyweights like Tearlaments, Branded and Runick.

Going first, it can set up it's grindgame Shangri-Ira (a resource generator every Standby-phase) and several interruptions such as Wandering Gryphon Rider's omni-negate, Fenrir's banish and Dogmatika Punishment's destruction.

Going second, this deck can plough through interruptions and beatdown monsters with its beefy free special summons of high attack monsters. Fenrir itself can take out 2 cards for the price of 1, while searching another Kashtira from deck (no wonder it's limited lol)!

The release of Kashtira from Rage of Chaos truly begins a new era of Masterduel ladder - one of fieldwide lockdowns and banishment.

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
This current iteration of Kashtira is played with several supporting engines since it doesn't have the capability to stand on it's own without it's second wave of support. Therefore, the Adventure package, Dogmatika package, and a tiny Hero and Superpoly package are included.
 
The Adventure package facilitates the summon of rank 7 monsters, helping to bring out bosses like Mind Hacker, Big Eye, and most importantly, Shangri-Ira. The Adventure package also helps clear the board of threats through the bounce of Dracoback and Illegal Knight. Wandering Gryphon Rider's omni-negate helps insulate the strategy from any interruptions or negates as well.
 
The Dogmatika package is used because the Extra Deck has space to spare. It is used in this strategy to break the board with Nadir Servant (send N'tss to pop 1) and gain advantage (Garura's +1 draw and Ecclessia's search). Ecclessia + Fleurdelis push out quite a bit of damage as well, ultimately attacking for 5000ATK during the battle phase.
 
2 Instant Contacts are included to summon a relatively free level 7 Elemental Hero Sunrise to the board for rank 7 plays.

3 Super Polymerizations and its targets are included in the Extra Deck, since this strategy has lots of Extra Deck space. Super Poly breaks most boards right now, allowing the duelist to play through established boards even more going second.
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
There is no current "combo" right now with this iteration of Kashtira since it lacks its second wave of support. Kashtira in its present form is a "midrange beatdown aggro" deck, able to break boards easily, gather lots of resources and play a simple grindgame.

Currently, the gameplan going first is creating Shangri-Ira and gain as much advantage as possible by establishing the Kashtira spells/traps, Adventure Engine, Dogmatika Engine, setting Super Poly, Called By, etc. while keeping handtraps in hand. In the rare case you manage to summon 4 level 7s in one turn, you can make both Shangri-Ira + Mind Hacker so you can start locking some zones and banishing your opponent's deck.

Going second, this deck has a plethora of board breakers both in-archetype and with supporting engines. Fenrir's target banish, Adventure Engine's bounces with Illegal Knight + Dracoback, Nadir Servant's pop by sending N'Tss and Superpoly's fusion can crack boards easily. In the battle phase, you can use your big special summoned monster's to clear your opponent's board. This strategy easily generates 8000+ damage on board to attack for game! If you haven't finished off your opponent, you can then proceed to the usual "going first" strategy of summoning Shangri-Ira.

GENERAL TIPS
  • This strategy excels at cracking established boards. Be methodical on how you break boards with this deck. After carefully breaking your opponent's board and baiting out interruption, you can then proceed to make this deck's current win-condition, Shangri-Ira.
  • Keep in mind If you special summon Kashtira Riseheart from hand with it's own effect, you'll lock yourself into XYZ!
  • Remember that using Nadir Servant and Ecclesia will lock you from the Extra deck for the rest of the turn! Similarly, using Dogmatika Punishment will lock you for 2 turns!
  • Keep in mind that when you use Rite of Aramesir, it prevents you from using a normal summoned monster's effect. The only monster this really affects is Psi-Beast, who needs to be normal summoned. If you have both in hand, you can only use one.
  • When using Pot of Prosperity, the only cards I don't recommend banishing are Shangri-Ira and Baronne. Keep in mind which cards in the Extra deck you need for the current cards you have in your hand!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
A new down rises in the Masterduel meta, and it is in the shade of crimson red! Kashtira makes its debut, ready to forever change how Yugioh is played with it's banishment effects, gigantic special summoned beatsticks, resource generation and most of all - FIELD LOCKDOWN!

This deck is only a weak precursor of what's to come - and I for one can't wait for Kashtira to be at full power so that it can invade and oppress ladder!

I'll also make more variants of Kashtira decks in the near future and an accompanying guide - stay tuned!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, a plush toy called "Frightfur Leo" wants to love your opponent, even after death! Scary, ain't it? I guess it wouldn't hurt explaining the plan to you.

 

(What a cute toy!)

 

Gameplan

1) Let "Black Garden" plant a rose to your opponent's side and replace it with Jizukiru. If your opponent goes first and places a monster, there should be no need for "Black Garden".

2) Set your opponent's LP to 3000 with Linewalker. Just don't play "Upstart Goblin" afterwards and you will be fine.

3) To bring forth "Frightfur Leo", have "Polymerization" + "Edge Imp Saw" + "Fluffal Penguin" in your hand. Then, simply play "Polymerization" and use other two monsters in-hand as materials to Fusion Summon "Frightfur Leo".

4) Finally, target Jizukiru to FTK your opponent. Note that Leo will inflict damage to your opponent equal to original attack of Jizukiru, not modified one due to "Black Garden". Therefore, 3300 damage will always be dealt to your opponent, no question about it.

deck_excerpt: "Take care of all your memories. For you can(not) relive them"
deck_description:
Mementos is a control/OTK Deck focusing on destroying their names to fill the GY, granting you effects if you do. They also don't share a type meaning this Deck can run There Can Be Only One without much problem.

Mementoral Memorial:

  • Memento Dark Blade is a Level 4 Dark Warrior, meaning it can be searched with Reinforcement of the Army, on Summon you Discard 1 "Memento" card to pop a Spell/Trap, meaning you get to force stuff like Infinite Impermanence or stopping cards like Swordsoul Blackout, you do need to be careful cause if you dont have Memento Tatsunootoshigo, One for One or Memento Bone Party your turn can straight up end here. Dark blade can destroy a "Memento" on field to Emergency Teleport a Level 3 or lower "Memento" Monster, usually Memento Fairywitch since she is our starter. On the topic of E-telis Mementos have their own in Memento Bone Party blowing up a Memento which allows for GY set-up from hand and to dodge effects like Imperm or Veiler.
  • Memento Fairywitch is our Elemental HERO Stratos searching on Summon a "Memento" Monster, she can target a Level 2 or lower "Memento" in the GY, and then blows up a "Memento" Monster to summon it. She is crucial for most of your combos which rely on Memento Goblin or Memento Mace. You will usually have 2 of her in the GY cause of the next card, which is important for the boss monster to work properly.
  • Memento Tatsunootoshigo can Special Summon himself from your Hand if you control no Monsters or if you control a "Memento". He can blow up a "Memento" and then Foolish Burial monsters whose total Levels are lower or equal to the destroyed Monster, so destroying Tatsunoo means you can get Mace, Witch and Goblin in the GY, this card has interesting set-ups with their Field Spell Netherskull Temple - Mementoran which can revive one of the sent Monsters as long as their level is lower than the one destroyed.
  • Memento Goblin can also benefit of Mementoran, this little Fiend can discard itself if you control a Mementoral Tectolica, the Netherskull Dragon to Miscellaneousaurus, but his more used effect would be the ability to Destroy another name to Foolish any 2 "Memento" cards which do include their backrow, which Mementoran sets back on the field during the Endphase. You do run him at one since he is a garnet and you really want to get him in the GY with Tatsu.
  • Memento Mace like Goblin has a handtrap effect if you control Tectolica, being able to Change of Heart a Monster, which pairs well with I:P Masquerena and S:P Little Night. She like the other Mementos can blow up another "Memento" Monster to fetch any archetypal card. Not much to say other than she is your usual One for One target.
  • Memento Horn Dragon can summon himself if you have 3 differently named Mementos in the GY or Field. If he is Destroyed he gets to blow up 3 cards on the field including 1 Memento, this also synergizes with the Field being able to Summon stuff in the opponent's turn, Memento Fracture Dance is the best match for this guy, being able to blow up to 5 cards if you have Tectolica. Fracture's GY effect facilitates the OTK efforts.You run 1 cause its just a body that does nothing.
  • Now to the Big Bad Boss which has one of the coolest artworks in-game as of recent time, Mementoral Tectolica, the Netherskull Dragon, this big boy has 5K ATK/DEF, being able to beat over most things in game, his condition to be summoned is either shuffling 5 differently named "Memento" Monsters from your GY or Hand back to the Deck or Extra Deck... or Memento Bone Back (Which is not the best card but eh) If you just control this guy he can attack all monsters your opponent controls, pair that with Bone Party and you get piercing damage, and if your opponent activates a card/effect you get to reborn a "Memento" meaning you can Destroy S/T with Blade, get Goblin/Mace via Witch or blow stuff up with Horn. Incredible boss monster. His power grows even more when powered by Memento Cranium Burst which lets him Negate up to 5 monster effects that activate on the field, while also forcing your opponent to crash onto him.

Basic Combo: Witch/DarkBlade/Party in hand

Blade destroys himself summoning Witch from Deck > Witch effect adds Tatsunoo > Tatsunoo Special Summons himself > Tatsunoo targets himself sending Goblin, Mace and Witch to the GY > Witch effect blows herself up summoning Goblin > Goblin destroys himself sending any card you want + Tectolica, do send Cranium or Fracture if you have the Fieldspell > Tectolica effect shuffles 5 summoning itself. Next turn you can summon back the Witch and you can get Mace or Goblin

Pot of Prosperity can be ran instead of Pot of Extravagance

deck_excerpt: It just so happens that Turbulance is a Level 9
deck_description:
I swear that all of these Prediction Princess brews these couple of days are not me trying to cope with the fact that Amazement got Amazement Abomination Arlekino (a CYAC card) in Master Duel but the Prediction Princess DABL support was passed on. TRUST ME! Like I can understand the PHHY cards in Chaos and the Kash support outside of DABL. The Chaos stuff is really cool, especially with P.U.N.K. and the Bystials, and the Kash support sufficiently supports the Kash stuff from DABL without Arise-Heart breaking the format (even more), but why the one singular support card (and the only Amazement card in CYAC) from what is basically 2 sets in the future in the current timeline of releases? Like if you want to play a Trap Deck, just play Labrynth.

Rescue-ACE has multiple cards that act as 1-card starters now that the DUNE support has released, allowing it to end on Rescue-ACE Turbulance to set up to 4 backrow from Deck extremely easily. Coincidentally, Turbulance is also a Level 9 FIRE Machine, making it a prime target for World Legacy Monstrosity. I originally had no faith in the Rescue-ACE cards even working in the slightest with Prediction Princess, but it works to a surprisingly good degree. Sure, it's not the most optimal Deck, nor the most optimal build of Rescue-ACE, but having access to a 1-card combo starter and being able to branch out into even more plays later along the line gives this Deck a surprising amount of versatility. If you draw just the Rescue-ACE combo, play Rescue-ACE. If you draw just the Prediction Princess combo, play Prediction Princess. If you draw both, why not play both.

Main Deck: 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, and 2 Deus X-Krawler. Tarotreith can be summoned off of Tarotrei and its flip effect allows you to summon a flip from Deck face-down and it has another effect to flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down as a Quick Effect. Tarotrei summons a flip from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase and it is a Quick Effect to either flip a monster face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse adds a Prediction Princess and a Ritual Spell from Deck on flip, summons itself back face-down when tributed, and it gives all of your Rituals targeting and destruction protection against your opponent's effects. We are not playing Pot of the Forbidden because Turbulance replaces it as a target for Monstrosity. It does turn off your ability to use very powerful equalizing effects later on in the game when it comes down to resource management, but for the most part, I think that you are well off sitting on Deus X and protecting it to prevent your opponent from making plays involving monsters. In addition to that, it does reduce the amount of variety in your flip plays, so if you really wanted, you could add in 1 Pot or some other flip to make things more interesting. 2 Rescue-ACE Turbulance which can be summoned from hand by banishing 2 Rescue-ACE cards from grave. During your Main Phase, it can set up to 4 Rescue-ACE Quick Play Spells/Normal Traps from your Deck and if another card(s) you control leaves the field by your opponent's card effect, you can pop a card on the field. Being able to set up to 4 backrow in addition to your Prediction Princess plays gives you more variety in your interruptions and interactions on your opponent's turn to deal with different threats that may come your way or to deal with any of your opponent's cards that play through your Prediction Princess/Flip monsters. Also, Turbulance doesn't have a restriction to how you summon it, making it an easy summon off of World Legacy Monstrosity by targeting something like Tarotrei or Bibliomuse, giving you easy access to it setting 4 backrow from Deck. Also, because of how easy it is to access off of your 1-card starters in Rescue-ACE, it is extremely easy to get Bibliomuse and Deus X onto the field via Monstrosity targeting Turbulance on field. You would then overlay Deus X and Turbulance for Aggregator, sending Herald for a Ritual search and attaching and Linking it off for another search. You now have access to Tarotrei and Bibliomuse to Tribute for the Ritual Summon with then gives you access to Tarotreith after you summon it back and flip it face-up. 2 Rescue-ACE Preventer which can summon itself from hand by banishing 1 Rescue-ACE card from grave. If you control another Rescue-ACE monster, it's a Quick Effect to book a monster your opponent controls and if its sent to grave, you can special a banished Rescue-ACE except for a Level 8. Extremely good card. It has a much easier way to summon itself compared to the other lower level Rescue-ACE's in a non-pure Rescue-ACE Deck. In addition to that, it has a very good form of interruption in the form of flipping an opponent's monster face-down and it can even get back a banished Rescue-ACE when it's sent to GY, being something like Hydrant to get your additional effects/options or Turbulance for a Level 9 for yourself to go into more Rank 9 plays. 3 Rescue-ACE Air Lifter which we are pretyt much only playing for its first effect. On Normal or Special Summon, it adds a Rescue-ACE Spell from Deck. This gets you EMERGENCY! which is basically E-Tele for the Deck, giving you access to Hydrant for Turbulance with 2 Rescue-ACE cards in grave to banish to summon said Turbulance. 3 Rescue-ACE Hydrant. Your opponent can't target it for attacks or with effects if you control another Rescue-ACE, it allows you to activate a Rescue-ACE Quick Play or Trap that was set by an effect during the same turn (opt), and it can search a Rescue-ACE from Deck. Hard drawing this card still is good as it gives you access to Preventer if you Link it off to put in grave. However, it still is somewhat better to summon it from Deck with EMERGENCY! to better get sufficient material in grave to summon a Turbulance you search off of it. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Reinforcement of the Army for Air Lifter. 1 One for One for Hydrant. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Rituals a Prediction Princess from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from grave during the Standby Phase to Special a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity. This Deck is not wholly reliant on it as you can still just play Rescue-ACE if you don't have sufficient access to Prediction Princesses. However, it is a good card to get Rank 9 plays going and to access your Prediction Princess combo. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 ALERT! which adds a Rescue-ACE from grave or can add a Rescue-ACE from Deck if you control Hydrant. 1 RESCUE! which summons a Rescue-ACE from grave or can Special a monster from your opponent's grave if you control Hydrant. 3 EMERGENCY! which Summons a Rescue-ACE from Deck then requires you to Tribute a Rescue-ACE from hand or field. Then, you can banish it from grave during your Main Phase to set a Rescue-ACE Trap from Grave. This card gives you extremely easy access to the whole Rescue-ACE line, especially if you search it off of Air Lifter as it gets you Hydrant while also putting enough material in grave for Turbulance. 1 EXTINGUISH! which can destroy an effect monster your opponent controls if you control a Rescue-ACE and prevent your opponent from activating effects of that monster or monsters with the same original name for the rest of the turn if you control Hydrant. CONTAIN! which negates the effects of an effect monster your opponent controls, making it also unable to attack, and if you control Hydrant, it cannot be used as Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, or Link material for the rest of the turn. It might seem overkill to have the Rescue-ACE Traps in addition to Deus X negating the activations of your opponent's monsters. However, the thing about Deus X is that it doesn't stop Continuous Effects. Like if your opponent makes Bagooska, what the heck are you doing against that? The Traps help insulate against those types of effects.

Extra Deck: 2 Herald of the Arc Light for Ritual searches when sent off of Aggregator. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Stellar Nemesis T-PHON - Doomsday Star. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer which I think is a really cool card for Rank 9 Decks that works really well with T-PHON. You can detach any number of materials from it to target the same number of cards on the field and destroy them which is a pretty good way to clear cards off the field going second. Then, you can overlay it for T-PHON to detach 1 and bounce a monster on the field to the hand, and you will always be able to use Earth Slicer for material because it having 3100 ATK makes it always the largest thing in your Deck. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. You've probably heard me praising this thing day and night already for being able to send Herald from Extra Deck for a Ritual search when you Xyz Summon it, with it being able to reattach said Herald from grave for another search when you Link off Aggregator. It's just so good for a Ritual Deck that happens to be able to make Rank 9's. 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows for a choice of interruption or board clearing if you have the material for a Rank 9 on board. 1 Nine-Lives Cat which can detach 1 to Summon a Level 9 from your grave or a monster from your opponent's grave. 1 Knightmare Unicorn. 1 S:P Little Night. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Linkuriboh. And 1 Gravity Controller.

For the Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Cosmic Cyclone, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Called by the Grave, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Solemn Judgment.

deck_excerpt: Lock up that extra deck, baby!
deck_description:
DRACOSLAYER

GOAL

What we aim to accomplish in this build. We want to end on Spheres, Dinoster Powered, Hope Harbinger, and a possible rank 4. We are also aiming to use Zealantis to reset 1-2 copies of Ignister durning this combo.

Why are we aiming for this board? We want to get amorphage golliath out of the hand or deck with spheres & lock the extra deck thus stopping our opponent's plays; meanwhile, it will be passively protected by both Hope Harbinger & Dinoster Powered. 

CARDS WE SKIPPED OVER

We did NOT play Necrovalley, Secret Village, Zombie World, etc. We didn't play Odd-Eyes Arc Pend either.
We opted to base our list off the 2022 Japan Championship list and slightly evolve that list with more modern understandings of Dracoslayer. We don't want to get to greedy & want plans in case Maxx C gets activated. Total combo or bust is not the way to build.

CARDS THAT COULD BE ADDED

Another Amorphage scale. Something like Lechary to prevent spells from being activated while it is in scale. This can stop Super Poly, Dark Ruler, et all. A second Goliath to turn on its Macro Cosmos scale effect. Which ever Amorphage scale effect you could want is honestly what I would add here. This is simply the Day 1 build my chat & I came up with on the fly over on Twitch.

NOTES

The above linked video contains two different deck lists. THIS LIST & a Draco Face-off build. The Draco Face-off Build starts at 6:24. Everything prior is THIS list.

This Deck combines the "Tenyi" related cards along with "Phantasm Spiral" cards that center around "Phantasm Spiral Token" that is Special Summoned by the effects of "Phantasm Spiral Dragon" and "Pacifis, the Phantasm City." In order to activate effects like "Phantasm Spiral Battle," the monsters on your field must be only Normal Monsters. However, cards like "Tenyi Spirit - Shthana" haves effects that activate from your hand or Graveyard, making it easier to catch your opponent off guard. The key here will be striking after you've dealt with your opponent's card.

deck_excerpt: dracoslayer deck post new selection pack rage of chaos
deck_description: The full detailed version such as combo guide is available on Youtube

Several of the "Blue-Eyes" cards either don't care if they're in the hand or they want to be in the GY, like Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon and The White Stone of Ancients, so you can rasily discard them with the effect of Hugin the Runick Wings, to search the powerful "Runick" Field Spell, Runick Fountain. Fountain is the centerpiece of the Runick strategy, as it allows you to play the Runick Quick-Plays Spells from your hand anytime, and gains you immense card advantage while recurring your Runick cards.

Jet Dragon is crucial to this deck, as it not only protects your Runick Fountain while it's on the field, but can also Chain Block the effect to draw. For example,say Jet Dragon is your hand or grave while there is a Blue-Eyes White Dragon, and you activate a card like Runick Flashing Fire or Runick Destruction that destroys a card on the field, you would be able to activate the effect of Fountain to return Runick cards and draw as Chain LInk 1, and then subsequently activate the effect of Jet Dragon to summon itself as Chain Link 2, that way, cards like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring that can normally stop Fountain from drawing would be unable to be activated. With the destruction protection of Jet Dragon, Fountain becomes much more difficult to out, though cards like Cosmic Cyclone would work, however, this is especially effective when combined with the targeting protection of Munin the Runick Wings, which would prevent such tactics from stopping Fountain. This essentially makes non-targeting non-destruction removal, such as Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen, or non-targeting negation, like Herald of the Arc Light, the only ways to stop the card.

This deck is very interesing, and very fun, give it a try.

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes White Dragon, Fusion, Five Headed Dragon, Numeron Dragon.
Inspired by Farfa's Qliphort deck in Master Duel (but not an exact copy)
deck_description:
Finally, a deck that's one I love and that can actually beat some of the top decks (if you play really well)

That's right, its QLIPHORT TIME, BABY!

Explanation of the cards - this one's not as big as my last few guides

 

==The Boss Monsters==

Apoqliphort Towers

Yeah, you know the one. This card was banned for a long time, and for good reason. Despite needing not being able to be Special Summoned and needing 3 "Qli" tributes to Normal Summon or Set it, this card is crazy. It's unaffected by all activated monster effects from monsters that are level 9 or lower, and is immune to all Spell/Trap effects (keep in mind that if Skill Drain is face-up and you summon this, then Skill Drain does negate Tower's effects - but if Skill Drain is flipped after Towers is summoned then it does not affect Towers). Being able to possibly force your opponent to get rid of a card in their hand is also amazing (but this only is for monsters, and can activate Tearlament GY effects, so be careful of that). This and Skybase are literally the best walls in the deck against Runick - they will have no way of outing this without a kaiju or by battling it. Speaking of Skybase...

Apoqliphort Skybase

Same as Towers, but one level lower (Cannot be Special Summoned, 3 "Qli" tributes needed to Normal Summon/Set, unaffected by activated effects of monsters level 8 or lower, and mmune to all Spell/Trap effects [same thing with Skill Drain applies here]). The differece is, it lets you target and steal a monster your opponent controls until the end phase. Overall, just as good as Towers.

The Pendulum Monsters

Qliphort Scout

The best card in the deck - searchable with Summoner's Art (of which it can only add Scout or Monolith in this deck). Despite having no monster effect, the Pendulum effect is what makes this card amazing. For the simple cost of 800 LP, you can add any "Qli" card from your deck to your hand. Even better - this isnt a hard once per turn effect (meaning you can abuse this with Trampolynx). Being unable to Special Summon monsters except "Qli" monsters really isn't an issue in this deck, as you dont need the Extra Deck, except for Qliphort Genius (but that's a "Qli" card).

Qliphort Monolith

Searchable with Summoner's Art, but has no monster effect, like Scout. However, this card can literally let you draw 3 in the EP (if you tribute 3 "Qli" monsters while it's in your Pendulum Zone  - this is done with Towers or Skybase). Prioritise getting Scout over this card.

Qliphort Helix / Qliphort Carrier

These have basically the same effects - you can Normal Summon without tributing, but the level will become 4, and the original ATK becomes 1800. Difference is, if Helix is tributed, you can destroy a Spell/Trap on the field, and if Carrier is tributed, you can destroy a monster. The Pendulum effects just prevent you from Special Summoning anything that's not a "Qli" monster and either give all your "Qli" monsters 300 extra ATK or make all your opponent's monsters on the field lose 300 ATK). These cards are also unaffected by monster effects from monsters whose level/rank is lower than its current level if they are Normal Summoned/Set  If Skill Drain affects these cards, their levels will go back to 8 and their ATK will go back to 2400 - as their effect which causes the changes is negated.

Qliphort Stealth, Disk, and Shell

Same effect as Carrier and Helix (can Normal Summon with tributing, but makes them level 4, original ATK 1800), but they also have unique effects that happen only when they are Tribute Summoned by tributing a "Qli" monster(s).

Stealth - You can target a card on the field and return it to the hand (this effect cannot be responded to by your opponent)

Shell - Can make a second attack in each Battle Phase and does piercing battle dmg if it attacks a monster in defense position

Disk - You can Special Summon 2 "Qli" monsters from your deck but destroy them during the end phase (this is the best one in my opinion)

Shell's Pendulum effect causes all monsters your opponent controls to lose 300 ATK, whereas Stealth and Disk give your "Qli" monsters on the field 300 extra ATK.

Performapal Trampolynx

"Oh my god, trampolynx, trampolynx" - Farfa

Anyways, Trampolynx's Pendulum effect lets you return a card in your Pendulum Zone to your hand when you Pendulum Summon. This is best used to return Qliphort Scout, which you can then activate again, and use the Pendulum effect to add any "Qli" card from your deck to your hand. You can also just Normal Summon it to bounce the Scout too, but that's lame, and it stops you from Normal Summoning the "Qli" monsters that turn. Use either of these effects to abuse Qliphort Scout as much as possible.

The Spells and Traps

Saqlifice

Makes the "Qli" monster you equip it to unable to be destroyed by battle, gives it 300 ATK, and it can be treated as 2 tributes for the Tribute Summon of Towers or Skybase. Even better, if it goes from the field to the GY, you can add a "Qli" monster from your Deck to your hand. If you can abuse this effect, do so.

Re-Qliate

This is temporary Skill Drain for Normal Summoned level 4 or lower monsters, and level 5 or higher Special Summoned monsters (only negates until the end of the turn). This card can be very helpful depending on the matchup - e.g. this card is pretty good against Kashtira, but HORRIBLE against Spright and Purrely.

Summoner's Art

Literally here for adding Qliphort Scout or Monolith. No other purposes.

Pot of Extravagance

You don't need your Extra Deck (other than Qliphort Genius), so this card is almost a must use (either this or Prosperity). Easy draw 2 effect, but will stop you from drawing with Monolith in the EP (if you even are able to use Monolith's effect).

Skill Drain

This card is OP in this deck - it allows your Qliphorts to be a 2400 or 2800 ATK Normal Summon. Oh, and it affects your opponent too, so that's a plus.

Lose 1 Turn

This card is insane against decks that like to Special Summon monsters a lot, and there's a lot of them - Spright, Purrely, Kashtira, Dragon Link, etc...

It negates the effects of monsters the turn they are Special Summoned, and changes effect monsters to defense position if they are Special Summoned in attack position - this reminds me of a certain generic Rank 4 Xyz Monster that does almost the same thing, but better - any guesses as to what it is?

Gozen Match

Forces each player to control only 1 attribute of monster. This card can single-handedly win you games against certain decks - e.g. Kashtira, Sky Striker, etc.... best part is, this card doesn't affects you since 99.99% of the time you'll have EARTH monsters (all the Qliphorts are EARTH)

 

==The Extra Deck==

I'll only be going over one card here - the only one you'll usually need to use in games

Qliphort Genius

You need two machine monsters to Link Summon this, and if you do, it is unaffected by Spell/Trap effects and the effects of other Link monsters. You can use its effect to negate the effects of 1 card you control and 1 card your opponent controls (until the end of the turn), and also has another effect, where if two monsters are Special Summoned at the same time to both zones it points to, you can add a level 5 or higher machine monster from your Deck to your hand (another way to search Towers or Skybase).

 

The rest of the Extra Deck cards are just generic ones you see in a lot of decks, so there's no point in explaining them.

As usual, the side deck cards are self explanatory, as you see them a lot.

 

Alright, that's my decklist and guide to Qliphorts. Thanks to Farfa for inspiring this list (no it's not an exact copy of his) :)

As always, if you have any problems, queries, or improvements, tell me in the comments! I wish you a good day/night and the rest of your day.
