deck_excerpt: Frightfur Cruel Whale is a Level 9 TrollDespair
deck_description:
Remember when you used to overlay 2 Frightfur Cruel Whale into VFD? Well, now you can use those Level 9 Cruel Whales for something else: as a target for World Legacy Monstrosity and as material for Mereologic Aggregator. This isn't so much of a "Fluffal" Deck. It more aims to utilize the Fluffal and Frightfur cards to Deckthin and draw cards using Toy Vendor and Fluffal Wings then allowing you to make Frightfur Cruel Whale, giving you access to a 9. Then, if you have Herald of the Arclight for Trias Hierarchia for another 9 or have World Legacy Monstrosity, you can go into the Rank 9 Aggregator to send Herald, search a Ritual, reattach it, Link it off, and search a Ritual again. You are not ending on any notable means of actual Fluffal/Frightfur cards or any of their specific interruptions for your opponent's turn. The Fluffal cards are being used as an engine to deckthin and draw as well as get a Level 9 on field to be absolutely clear.

 Main Deck: Starting with the Fluffals and Edge Imps, 3 Fluffal Bear, 3 Edge Imp Chain, 1 Edge Imp Sabres, 1 Edge Imp Scythe, 1 Fluffal Owl, and 1 Fluffal Wings. Bear sends itself form hand to grave to set a Toy Vendor from Deck. Toy Vendor is extremely important for drawing and deckthinning in this Deck, so having more ways to access it is always good. Chain adds a Frightfur card from Deck when its sent from hand or field to grave. This can get you something like Frightfur Patchwork in order to further deckthin and give you access to more cards to start/further extend your plays. Or, it can search you Frightfur Fusion which is a good way to help you extend your plays in this Deck rather than for banishing a gazillion monsters to make a Frightfur Wolf that contests God himself and OTK your opponent into the sun. Notably, we are not playing Frightfur Repair to search off of Chain (or send off of Cruel Whale) because we are playing an extremely small amount of Fluffals, most of which are going to be banished out of the grave for Wings, therefore removing them from rotation. Sabres is another Edge Imp name, and in the case where you run out of Fluffals to search off of Toy Vendor, you also have the option to search Sabres from Deck. We aren't playing any notable Fusions that actually require it as material like Wolf, but it is better to have the 1 to search in case and to have another name in Deck. Edge Imp Scythe is not actually here to specifically Fusion on your opponent's turn for Cruel Whale for a pop. It is another name that you can search off of something like Patchwork, giving you more Edge Imps in rotation for Fusion plays on your turn. If you really wanted to, you could use it on your turn 0 to Fusion Cruel Whale for a pop when your opponent is the one going first as it gives you a Level 9 on field since you can banish it from grave to protect said Cruel Whale from destruction. Owl can be Summoned off of Diviner. This is just another way to Fuse to get to Cruel Whale, given you didn't draw Poly or Patchwork. There are some cases where you just don't Normal Summon in the Deck as a result of not drawing Diviner and having this in hand to Normal gives you Poly for Cruel Whale in a Level 9 or the Poly can be saved for next turn to make a Guardian Chimera that is untargetable and can pop and draw cards to help clear the board and gain resources. Wings is also Summonable off of Diviner and is usually the more optimal Summon target on a turn that you already have Cruel Whale or have a way to Fuse into it. It can banish itself from grave if you have Toy Vendor on field and banish another Fluffal from grave to draw a card and send said Toy Vendor to grave to draw another card. This would then trigger the Toy Vendor for a Fluffal or Edge Imp Sabres search which is not once per turn. If you are wondering why we are not playing some of the other Fluffal monsters, it's because we only have 5 Fluffal names in Deck that are absolutely necessary for this engine to work. The others focus a lot heavier on interacting with Fluffals in hand or ones in grave. We don't need them as they would just end up as bricks for the most part as they aren't exactly what we need for deckthinning and drawing to the best of our ability. For the other monsters, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, 2 Deus X-Krawler, 1 Trias Hierarchia, and 3 Diviner of the Herald. Tarotreith can be Ritual Summoned or Summoned with Tarotrei and it Summons a Flip from Deck face-down when its flipped and it is Quick Effect to flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Surprisingly, sometimes you end on 6 monsters on board, which means that if you wanted to use Tarotreith to summon a Flip from Deck, you'd have to Masquerena off a monster or two first. But that is all in the name of gameplay for the most part which is what we want. Tarotrei Summons a Flip from hand or grave face-down during your End Phase and it is a Quick Effect to flip a monster on field face-up or face-down. Bilbiomuse adds a Prediction Princess and a Ritual Spell from Deck on flip, it Summons itself back face-down when its tributed (which also happens to work with Hierarchia which is optimal in some situations to keep resources on board for more plays), and it makes all of your Rituals untargetable and indestructible by your opponent's effects. Deus X-Krawler negates all activated effects of your opponent's monsters on the field. It's the only realisitc Flip to Summon off of Tarotreith, but its all in good favor as you are ending on more than just Tarotreith and Tarotrei in this Deck. Hierarchia can Tribute a Fairy to Summon itself from hand or grave, giving you a Level 9 on field. If you Tribute Diviner, it triggers to Summon a Level 2 or lower Fairy from hand or Deck. If you Tribute Bibliomuse, it can Summon itself back face-down. Diviner can send a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to grave on Summon. Usually, you'd send Hierarchia to Tribute Diviner to Summon it. However, if you draw the Hierarchia, you can just send Arc Light from Extra and Tribute Diviner to Summon Hierarchia from hand.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction. This Rituals a Prediction Princess from hand or grave face-up or face-down and you can banish it from grave during the Standby Phase to get Bibliomuse from Deck face-down. 3 Toy Vendor which allows you to discard a card and draw a card. If that card is a Fluffal, you can Special Summon any monster from hand. If it's not, you discard it, an effect that is not a hard opt. If it's sent to grave, you can add a Fluffal or an Edge Imp Sabres from Deck which is not opt. This card is great for deckthinning and drawing, especially with Wings. 1 Frightfur Fusion which allows you to Fusion Summon a Frightfur by banishing monsters from field or grave. This usually gets you Frightfur Sabre-Tooth by using a Frightfur Fusion Monster you send from Extra Deck to grave with Cruel Whale and any other Fluffal or Edge Imp. Sabre-Tooth then Summons a Frightfur from grave, getting you back a Cruel Whale for a Level 9 on field. 3 Frightfur Patchwork which adds an Edge Imp and a Polymerization from Deck to hand which is excellent for getting resouces and deckthinning. The aforementioned 2 Polymerization, 3 World Legacy Monstrosity, and 3 Foolish Burial Goods to send Toy Vendor. 

Extra Deck: 1 Guardian Chimera which can be made on turn 3 for pops and draws with a Poly that you drew previously or searched during your previous turn. Coincidentally, it's also Level 9 meaning that you can also further go into Rank 9 or Prediction Princess plays afterwards if you wanted to. 2 Frightfur Cruel Whale which pops a card on both fields on Fusion Summon, and it can send a Frightfur card from Deck or Extra Deck to have a Fusion you control gain ATK equal to half its original ATK until the end of the turn. The send is usually a Frightfur Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck to get material in grave for Frightfur Fusion to make Sabre-Tooth. Also, it's a Level 9 whose Type and Attribute are good for World Legacy Monstrosity. 1 Frightfur Sabre-Tooth which Special Summons a Frightfur from grave on Fusion Summon. This gives you a Level 9 for Rank 9 plays and Sabre-Tooth itself is material for a Link Summon. 1 Frightfur Tiger. This is the card you'll be sending from Extra with Cruel Whale. It realistically can be any Frightfur Fusion Monster, but I just felt like in a wierd situation, this card would be the best Fusion to have in Extra just in case. 2 Herald of the Arc Light for Ritual searches. 3 Mereologic Aggregator which sends Herald from Extra for a Ritual search and can reattach it from grave, giving you another Ritual search if you Link Aggregator off. 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows. Frequently, you have enough resources and material on board during your standard combo to go into both Aggregator to send Herald and another Rank 9. Laevateinn is a great form of interruption on your opponent's turn which can also deal with certain matchups that Deus X cannot deal with like backrow Decks. I think you could play another Rank 9 in something like Phantom Fortress Enterblathnir or Sacred Tree Beast, Hyperyton in situations where you have more resources on board for another Rank 9. 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 S:P Little Night, 1 I:P Masquerena which you frequently are able to go into to both Link off Aggregator and have an interruption on your opponent's turn, and 1 Linkuriboh to get Wings into grave from field in certain situations. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Cosmic Cyclone, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Infinite Impermanence, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Solemn Judgment.

Hi! Today, we will glow our opponent in the afterlife. Let me show you how...

 

(What a glowing blow!)

 

Gameplan

1) When you find "Afterglow", play it. Then, set your opponent's LP to 3000 with Linewalker. As long as you don't play more than 1 x "Upstart Goblin", you will be fine.

2) When you discard Arcana with Ravenous, place "Light Barrier" and bring Arcana back to life with "Monster Reborn". Set the outcome to heads to skip your opponent's turn, at the cost of two of your monsters, which shouldn't be difficult.

  • In case you wonder, don't use Angel O1. Reason is that, if you check this link, you will notice that "Card Advance" and "Angel O1" fall into same category. Therefore, you can't stack "Card Advance" and "Angel O1" but you can either try my "Monster Reborn" tactic as explained above or with "Double Summon" because it falls into Group 1.

3) When you have "Afterglow" in your hand, play "A Feather of the Phoenix" to discard "Afterglow" and place it on top of your deck afterwards.

4) You can end your turn whenever you are ready. Just don't forget to send two of your monsters to GY to skip your opponent's turn with Arcana.

5) It's your turn now. You will draw "Afterglow" thanks to setup you did at #3 and 4000 damage will be done to your opponent to finish them.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial. 30 UR saved, off to a good start!

- "Into The Void" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 480 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Raidraptor - Stranger Falcon FTK ft. Panda+Linewalker+Jizukiru
deck_description:
It's time for aerial assault with Raidraptors. A stranger falcon is looking for a hidden strike right into your opponent's face. Let's not keep it waiting, for that I have a good plan, after all.

 

(Time for aerial assault!)

 

Gameplan

1) Plant a rose to your opponent's side with "Black Garden" and burn it with Jizukiru.

2) Set your opponent's LP to 3000 via Linewalker. Just don't play "Upstart Goblin" afterwards and you will be fine.

3) Bring forth Number 60. There are two ways you can do it:

  • Cthugua + Cthugua = Number 60
  • Saryuja >>> Level 4 monster >>> Panda + Monk = Number 60

4) Then, play "Rank-Up-Magic Raid Force" to bring forth "Raidraptor - Stranger Falcon" by targeting Number 60 as pre-requisite.

5) Finally, let Falcon target Jizukiru to one-shot your opponent. Note that Falcon will deal original attack of your opponent's monster as damage, not modified one due to "Black Garden". Therefore, 3300 damage will be done to your opponent, no need to worry about it.

deck_excerpt: Dark Jesse Anderson, Advanced Crystal Beasts
Nurse Burn FTK ft. Panda+Primal Seed
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, we will play a Nurse Burn deck but Panda and Chaos will be also involved to turn this deck into a FTK setup. Generally speaking, if you look at "Side Deck", these are cards Nurse Burn players utilize. As you can see, most of them are Trap cards. You are free to include them as well, or change the deck altogether, but why wait for another turn to flip all traps when you can cure your opponent on the very first turn itself? I guess it's time to explain how to FTK with our beloved Nurse.

 

(Panda and Nurse are caring our guest well!)

 

Gameplan

1) Draw your deck until you find all combo pieces needed. They are:

  • Darklord Nurse Reficule + Upstart Goblin
  • Chaos Emperor Dragon + Primal Seed
  • ME-PSY-YA + A Feather of the Phoenix

2) To bring forth Nurse, either do it with "Double Summon" or with "Saryuja". Saryuja can Special Summon Nurse, that's why.

3) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon".

4) If you have at least a Main Deck monster in your GY, play "A Feather of the Phoenix" and discard a Main Deck monster. Then, place it on top of your Main Deck.

5) Play "Upstart Goblin" to convert healing into damage with Nurse to inflict 1000 damage to your opponent.

6) Here is the endless setup to FTK with Nurse:

  • First, play first "Primal Seed" to target "Upstart Goblin" + "A Feather of the Phoenix" and add them from Banish Zone (BZ) to your hand.
  • Then, play Phoenix to discard and place a monster on top of your deck. Afterwards, play "Upstart Goblin".
  • Next, play second "Primal Seed" to fetch first "Primal Seed" and "Upstart Goblin". Play "Primal Seed" for another time to get other "Primal Seed" and Phoenix.
  • Rinse and repeat what was explained in #4 and #5 until your opponent is dead. Don't forget to retrieve said cards with "Primal Seed".

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 570 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Despia falls to the dragon menace Albaz.
deck_description: Deck go brrrrrr. Albaz goes super saiyan.

Gameplan

Going second deck.

Your main win conditions are Gren Maju Da Eiza, Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying and Number 100: Numeron Dragon and swing for lethal.

You need to clear the opponents negates and destructions first, with cards like Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju & other kaijus, Super Polymerization or Interrupted Kaiju Slumber .

If going first, take trap cards from your side deck depending on what deck you are facing, if possible, then aim to finish your first turn with Super Polymerization set and Baronne de Fleur on the board. Then pray.

 

Unusual card choices and why :

Ruddy Rose Dragon : To prevent any graveyard shenanigans.

Crimson Dragon : If Chengying is negated or Baronne used all her effects, send them back to the extra and summon Ruddy Rose Dragon or Bystial Dis Pater to summon a banished monster and have a monster negate.

Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max : When your lvl 10 synchro are not enough to finish the game, summon this bad boy on main 2.

Foolish Burial : Gizmek Orochi and Plaguespreader Zombie effect on command.

Blackwing - Sharnga the Waning Moon : Cool-ass owl.

Only playing 2 Gren Maju Da Eiza because it's the biggest brick when drawn twice and we have a lot of card draw.

 

Tips

Interrupted Kaiju Slumber can be countered by Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring but only tell your opponent if they ask nicely.

Alpha, the Master of Beasts can be used to return one of your kaiju to your hand from the opponent field, to use it on another monster or to clean after Interrupted Kaiju Slumber .

If Number 100 and his 9000 attack won't be enough to close the game, you can play The Zombie Vampire before and pray to be able to summon a lvl 8 or a Tuner monster with its effect. Now your big dragon will have 17000 attack and I sure hope it's enough.

If you go first and play There Can Be Only One , you can play around it on your second turn but you have some duplicate types so be aware.

If you get Droll & Lock Bird on your turn, get better at the game.

Share this deck with other Gren Maju enjoyers.

deck_excerpt: Say goodbye to your zones!!! Muwahahahahaha!!!!!!
Number 6 FTK ft. Panda+Final Flame+Primal Seed
deck_description:
Welcome! It's time to purge the Atlantis with a final flame. If you are interested, keep reading.

 

Gameplan

- Before we start, it would be for your benefit to read through what I call "Synchro Chain Train", where you can Synchro Summon monsters in a successive order to draw your deck...

1) If you open up with Monk >>> Panda, this is how you can play with...

  • Assuming that you have always spells to draw, this is how: Monk + Tuner = Librarian >>> Tuner + Non-Tuner = Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Martial >>> Martial brings Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Integrator >>> Martial + Integrator = Stardust >>> Stardust (Tuner due to Martial) + Non-Tuner = Ancient >>> Ancient pulls Level 1 Tuner >>> Ancient + Tuner = Accel >>> Accel pulls Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Shamisen >>> Shamisen + Non-Tuner = Cthugua >>> Accel + Tuner = Ravenous
  • Assuming that there is a chance you might brick, this is how: Monk + (Tuner + Non-Tuner = Formula) = Stardust >>> Stardust + Tuner = Ancient >>> Ancient pulls Panda/Monk to continue the chain with Librarian and other Synchro monsters.

2) If you start only with Panda, this is how you can play with:

  • Tuner + Non-Tuner = Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Martial >>> Martial brings Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Integrator >>> Martial + Integrator = Stardust >>> Stardust (Tuner due to Martial) + Non-Tuner = Ancient >>> Ancient pulls Panda/Monk to continue the chain with Librarian and other Synchro monsters.

 

- Time to explain the FTK setup with Number 6...

1) Reach the situation as illustrated:

  • Raidraptor was XYZ Summoned by using Nemeses + Cthugua as materials. Number 13 was XYZ Summoned by using 2 x Level 1 monsters as materials.
  • It's important to have these XYZ monsters on the battlefield because we will deliver them to GY as Link materials for Saryuja.
  • "Final Flame" was used beforehand and banished by Panda.

 

2) Link Summon Saryuja by using 4 monsters as materials. Two of them must be Number 13 and Raidraptor, no matter what:

  • Although hard to see in this picture, after you have sent Number 13 + Raidraptor to GY, have those combo pieces below:
    • Chaos Emperor Dragon + Primal Seed
    • ME-PSY-YA + Back to Square One
    • Rank-Up-Magic Soul Shave Force + Final Flame
  • If you have banished one of "Primal Seed" and other combo spells mentioned above with either Monk or Ravenous, you can retrieve them back with Chaos Emperor Dragon. You will see what I mean.

 

3) First, Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. Then, place "ME-PSY-YA" on Pendulum Zone and play "Rank-Up-Magic Soul Shave Force":

  • Shave Force will bring Raidraptor back to life, with a follow up to Number 6.

 

4) Since this Special Summon caused by Shave Force also counts as XYZ Summon of Number 6, you can trigger its ability as usual:

  • We will repeat this step as many times as we can until we find the lethal range of "Final Flame" to burn our opponent alongside Atlantis.

 

5) Time to bounce Number 6 back to Extra Deck with "Back to Square One":

  • We have to bring Number 6 back to Extra Deck because Shave Force can only Special Summon a XYZ monster from Extra Deck.

 

6) Time to play "Primal Seed" cards. Our targets will be "Back to Square One" + "Shave Force" + "Final Flame" to retrieve them back to hand. You can cycle those cards forever by playing second "Primal Seed" and targeting first "Primal Seed" alongside aforementioned spells.

 

7) From here on:

  • Rinse and repeat what was explained in #4 to bring forth Number 6 to halve your opponent's LP.
  • Rinse and repeat what was explained in #5 to place Number 6 back to Extra Deck, so that you can repeat what was done in #4.

 

8) When you are within the lethal range of "Final Flame", play it to burn everything down alongside Atlantis. Victory is yours:

  • If you don't like "Final Flame", there are alternative options you can give it a shot in "Side Deck". Feel free to check but note that if you want to FTK with "Reversal Quiz" + "Fuhma Shuriken" setup thanks to "Back to Square One", you have to destroy ME-PSY-YA with Ravenous. Adding "Mystical Space Typhoon" is also an option because Pendulum Monsters are considered as Spell cards if placed on Pendulum Zones.
  • You can watch the deck in action by clicking here!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" Secret Pack to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number 6" can be found within "Timeworn Legacies" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Raidraptor - Force Strix" can be found within "Invulnerable Iron Wings" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_description: 1st Place YCS LA Edsion Top Fairy Deck

Chimera branded version with toolbox of handtraps and tech cards.

Nightmare magician is great going second. It allows you to steal a problematic monster/negation. At the same time, It can allow you to more than a pop without targeting.

The idea is to maximize illusionist engine without depending on the branded part plus a bunch of handtraps and utility cards to deal with the opponent.

Book of moon is used to defend from some decks and protect your monsters from negation targets (like veiler or impermanence).

King Tiger Wanghu is great against decks like Purrely, spright, Marincess and many others with low attack monsters. To bring it in, you must search it with berfomet and on your opponents turn, you use chimera fusion to have "chimera the king of phantom beast" in your GY and use its effect to special summon Wanghu.

Invader of darkness is also another good target for this same combo to play against runnick spright variants. Many other "locker" demons can be used in the same way.

deck_excerpt: Heroes having faith in the church and what God has given!
deck_description:
I really wanted to make a deck based around Doriado and her prayers. So here is my version and the cards that can support this notion.

Doriado: The prayers of the saints but catered to fit the yugioh-verse.

Heroes and Neo-Spacians: Church members from the humans in the yugioh-verse.

Ghost Sister: A nun, but also hoping that there is less sin the world.

Future Fusion: Faith in the future promised by God.

Generation Next: Leaving things to the next generation of believers.

Miracle Contact: Sometimes Jesus intervenes. Cool stuff happens.

World Legacy Succession: The knowledge of the importance of the Gospel that is passed down from generation to generation (the realities of the Levite priesthood and how that has been spread to others who are not considered a part of the Levites who originally housed the tabernacle) and what an individual's place in that is.

Emergency Call/A Hero Lives: When things get tough and you need a hand.

Emergency Provisions: Communion.

Grand Horn of Heaven: The good news.

Waboku: Trusting in God and walking in faith.

If you looked at the deck recipe, you may be wondering, "what the actual hell is that deck jesus christ it looks so weird and stuff." Well, you're not wrong. If you wish to be enlightened as I have, and learn how to play this deck, then click read more, as I have explanations for all the cards and their place in the deck.

Monsters

Most of the normal monsters are just there. I chose them due to their stats being better than the competition. The exceptions to this are most of the dark monsters, and Crowned by the World Chalice. You can summon Crowned by the World Chalice with Imduk the World Chalice Dragon, and the dark monsters are used to go into Number 65: Djinn Buster.

Spells

Unexpected Dai, Tri-Wight, Enchanting Fitting Room, and Silent Doom are all just your standard normal monster support. They just give you a ton of bodies which you can use to spam link monsters. Pot of Desires is used for draw power. This deck just mainly needs cards to work with, and Desires gives you those cards. Upstart Goblin is also run to get you the cards you need. Finally, Mystical Space Typhoon is just basic spell and trap removal.

Extra Deck

Number 65: Djinn Buster was added in after Crystron Halqifibrax got banned. It doesn't really do the same thing, but it gives you a negate, so I added it. Underworld Goddess of the Closed World is there because it's just a great card. I also added I:P Masquerena for a massive interruption during your opponents turn.

Borrelsword Dragon is there to hit things really really hard. Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess is there because it's really useful. Accesscode Talker is there to also hit things hard. I can't really say much more about these 3, but they're all very useful.

Triple Burst Dragon is just a link 3 body to help Accesscode hit things harder. Flash Charge Dragon is there because I thought it was cool. If you get a really good hand, you can bring out Apollousa and Flash Charge Dragon, and Flash Charge Dragon point at the opponents extra monster zone. This will destroy any link monsters they try to summon. Protector Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman  is there to help you get out Flash Charge Dragon.

Link Spider and Imduk the World Chalice Dragon are there for pretty much the same reasons. Firstly, they're combo extenders. Both of them let you get out more monsters on the field. Secondly, monsters like Borrelsword Dragon and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World require effect monsters to be summoned. But oh no! You only have normal monsters. Luckily, you can just link them away into Link Spider or Imduk the World Chalice Dragon and hooray! Now you have effect monsters you can use to summon your monsters.

Side Deck

Nibiru, the Primal Being, Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, and Lightning Storm are all pretty simple. They're there if you're going second.

Tyrant's Throes is there because if you're going first, and you can activate Tyrant's Throes, it will turn off the opponent. They can't normal or special summon any effect monsters. However, it doesn't get rid of any effect monsters already on the field. So you if you have a Borrelsword Dragon or something on your field, you can just annihilate them next turn. If you want, you can swap it out for Tyrant's Tirade, which instead prevents them from activating monster effects. I prefer Tyrant's Throes, but either one is fine. The reason it's in the side deck and not the main deck is because if you're going second, your opponent will have already summoned all their monsters, so it really has no use. It's just a completely dead card. Ontop of that, it's not like you'll use it every time you go first.

Deck made by DarkArmedDuelist.

You can find the deck list here: https://youtu.be/xhbiXZlPgsQ

And the test hands here: https://youtu.be/jbs0our1Mig

deck_excerpt: Despite Branded Fusion's semi-limit to 2, Branded currently is still one of the top contenders for August's 2023 Masterduel meta!
deck_description:
Despite all the metagame changes, Branded Fusion's semi-limit to 2 and introduction of new powerhouses, Branded currently is still one of the top contenders for August's 2023 Masterduel meta. Able to consistently make gigantic fusion beatsticks with board clearing capabilities backed by a solid resource grindgame, Branded is the ultimate aggro-beatdown deck. Pushed into meta relevance by Konami because of it's fan favourite status as the "lore" deck of series 12, Branded post Rage of Chaos is a fusion powerhouse capable of competing vs. heavyweights like Tearlaments and Spright!
 
However, Branded suffers from two major weaknesses: Ash Blossom (On esp. on Branded Fusion) and Nibiru. Lucklily, Nibiru doesn't get used much for now because it isn't very effective against Tearlaments and Spright, the two biggest meta threats. However, Ash Blossom is being used by 80%+ of decks played right now (According to Masterduel stats), especially because Maxx "C" basically renders Ash mandatory in top tier play.
 
This version of Branded somewhat alleviates Branded's weakness to ash by giving the pilot so much gas and plays to work with so that you can play through devastating handtraps and eventually out-resource your opponent! This "gas" variant of Branded can keep playing, even though Branded Fusion is negated! 
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
This core of this deck is composed of the traditional Branded and Despia cards. 3 Tragedy is included as a banish target for Allure of Darkness (essentially a +1!). Due to the semi-limit of Branded Fusion, the third copy has been replaced by a Springans Kitt, who can search the card. 
 
The Bystial package is relatively small, since there is hardly any space in the maindeck for staples. Lubellion is "searcheable" from deck since Branded Fusion dumps him to the GY, and Lubellion can summon itself from the GY by tributing the on-field Albion. Lubellion can activate from deck Branded Lost as protection/search power or Branded Regained as a potent resource generator with its +1 draw and summon from the GY of a Bystial monster.
 
The Frightfur package is included as another piece of "gas" in the deck - maintaining hand advantage since all the pieces search each other and giving access to Polymerization (a powerful boardbreaker with Guardian Chimera).
 
Fusion Deployment functions as a toolbox in this deck, since its 2 targets each serve a distinct function. Albaz can break boards when summoned, and Albaz + Super Poly cracks most boards with ease. If your opponent happens to field Dragon monsters, Albaz can contact fuse them away. Cartesia enables fusion summoning as a quick effect. Not only does she give access to Granguinol (which is a foolish burial), she can protect your activating monster effects on the field from targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler by quick fusing them away. 
 
The Maxx "C" package is played in this deck to both deter and abuse the win in the "Masterduel Maxx C minigame." Crossout Designator targets Ash, Maxx "C," Bystials, and Imperm which are the current most common handtraps. 
 
3 Super Poly and its fusion targets are placed in the Extra deck, enabling the pilot to smash through established boards. Super Poly is a game deciding card on it's own in certain common match-ups, especially vs. Spright, Dragonlink and Tearlaments. 
 
50 cards are used in this deck rather than around ~40 since every important piece (esp. Branded Fusion) is highly searchable anyways. 50 cards also reduces the likelihood of drawing garnets and bricks. This "gas" version of Branded is designed to draw alot, search alot, and to play alot to overwhelm any sort of interaction your opponent has whether it is Ash Blossom, Spright Red, or on-board interruption. The only handtrap this deck really has difficulty with is Droll & Lockbird, and nobody really plays it in Masterduel in the current metagame. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
This "Gas" variant of Branded is designed to play through your opponent's interruption to create gigantic fusion beatsticks and overwhelm with high ATK and massive resource generation. From testing during my ladder climb, I can say with confidence that most hands can play through Spright and Tearlament boards with due to it's draw power and board breaking capabilities. If given even a second of breathing space, your opponent will find that they are facing down a field full of powerful fusion monsters!
 
Branded Fusion is both a blessing and a curse for this strategy. The whole deck revolves around searching and resolving that card, and if it's negated, your further options are likely limited. Your obvious glaring chokepoint and weakness is Branded Fusion, so it is imperative that you can bait out the Ash Blossom or fusion summon Dragoon before you use the card. It is advisable to use every other card first like Frightfur Patchwork, Branded Opening or Lubellion so that you can bait out your opponent's Ash Blossom. Also, from experience playing the deck, I've discovered that people intentionally hold their Ash Blossom saving it for Branded Fusion - so if you don't have the card, you can bluff having it and just do all your searches/summons from deck!
 
If Branded Fusion ends up being negated, the second best board you can make is double Masquerade the Blazing Dragon which is often doable due to the Polyermizations, Cartesia and excess of fusion material available to the pilot. Most decks would be hard-pressed to out double tax Dragons before 5 effects!
 
End boards are very hand dependant, but here are the mainline combos:
 
Branded Fusion + Dark Monster + Discard = Mirrorjade (banish), Bystial Lubellion + Branded Regained (+1 Draw, reborn Bystial from GY), Set Branded in Red
  1. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, sending Albaz + Bystial Lubellion from deck.
  2. Fusion summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon by fusing Albaz + Dark Monster with Albion. Ideal dark monsters to banish are Tragedy (search) and Dramaturge (free body on field).
  3. Lubellion (discards for cost) fusion summons Mirrorjade by shuffling back Albaz from banished pile and Lubellion the Searing Dragon on the field.
  4. Summon Bystial Lubellion from the GY by tributing Albion.
  5. Activate Lubellion's card effect to activate from deck Branded Regained. Alternatively, you can activate from deck Branded Lost for further searches/fusion protection.
  6. End phase - set your Branded card of choice from deck. Ideally, you set Branded in Red so you can fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If you already have Branded in Red, you can set Branded Opening for further searches/protection from destruction. 
Aluber + Frightfur Patchwork = Mirrorjade (banish), Bystial Lubellion + Branded Lost (Search for Mercourier - monster negate), Set Branded in Red
  1. Activate Frightfur Patchwork, searching for Edge Imp Chain and Polyermization.
  2. Normal summon Aluber to search for Branded Fusion from deck. 
  3. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, sending Albaz + Bystial Lubellion from deck.
  4. Fusion summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon by fusing Albaz + Dark Monster with Albion. 
  5. Lubellion discards Edge Imp Chain and fusion summons Mirrorjade by shuffling back Albaz from banished pile and Lubellion the Searing Dragon on the field.
  6. Edge Imp Chain searches for another Frightfur Patchwork.
  7. Summon Bystial Lubellion from the GY by tributing Albion.
  8. Activate Lubellion's card effect to activate from deck Branded Lost. 
  9. Activate Polymerization fusing Aluber + Lubellion to summon Masquerade the Blazing Dragon. 
  10. Activate trigger effect of Branded Lost to search for Mercourier. 
  11. End phase - set your Branded card of choice from deck. Ideally, you set Branded in Red so you can fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If you already have Branded in Red, you can set Branded Opening for further searches/protection from destruction. 
Cartesia + Light/Dark monster + Either Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon = Search for any Branded card (Best to use if you're missing a particular Branded card, esp. Branded Fusion!)
  1. Activate Cartesia's effect to fusion summon Granguinol by using Cartesia + Light/Dark monster. If Saronir is in hand, you use Saronir instead.
  2. Granguinol sends to GY from deck Bystial Saronir. (Or Albion the Shrouded Dragon)
  3. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY Branded Retribution. 
  4. Bystial Saronir/Albion the Shrouded Dragon sends to GY your Branded spell/trap card of choice. 
  5. Banish Branded Retribution from GY to retrieve from GY your Branded spell/trap of choice.
Going first and uninterrupted, your opponent will likely contend with Mirrorjade's banish, a Branded Regained's resource generation, and a set Branded in Red. Depending on the hand, your opponent may also be dealing with Mercourier's monster negate, Masquerade's -600 burn, and Granguinol can summon Proskenion from the Extra Deck. If you're lucky, you also have a facedown Super Polymerization - a devasting turn ending card if used at the right time. Your hand will likely also be sizeable and ready with follow-up for next turn since Cartesia, Alba-Lenatus and Albion generate follow-up during the end phase.
 
Going second, Branded can smash through boards and force it's way past interruption to beat down your opponent's monsters with high ATK fusion monsters. Branded is naturally equipped with in-engine ways to play going second. Polymerization fusing into Guardian Chimera is a nigh-unstoppable juggernaut since it's effect is often chainblocked with the fusion material used for it's fusion summon and it is untargetable since you used Polymerization. If Branded Opening is on the field, it also can't be destroyed! Super Polymerization can fuse away most boards in today's meta, especially with Garura, only needing 2 monsters with the same type and attribute. A common ladder experience is fusing away your opponent's Spright Elf + Red/Carrot for Garura! Against the occasional Dragonlink deck, Albaz can contact fuse their problematic Dragons away like Borreload Savage Dragon and Borrelend Dragon into Alba-Lenatus. Just set Albaz and contact fuse everything away! 
 

GENERAL TIPS

 
  • Try to bait out Ash Blossom by your many searches/summons from deck before you use Branded Fusion. If you don't have Branded Fusion, your opponent will likely hold Ash Blossom in their hand waiting for it, so you can bluff having the card to search/summon all you want!
  • Branded lacks in-engine ways to remove backrow, except with Guardian Chimera. Backrow floodgates absolutely slaughter Branded, so if you're against an opponent using something like Rivalry of Warlords, it probably is time to proceed to next game.
  •  Guardian Chimera is the best card to crack open established boards. With it's untargetability, beefy 3300ATK/DEF statline and non-targeting destruction, most boards fall to this offensive juggernaut. If your opponent negates Polymerization/Branded in Red to prevent Chimera from coming out, they have wasted a precious interaction paving the way for you to use Branded Fusion.
  • Try to have Cartesia on board before you summon monsters on the field with important effects. Cartesia's quick effect fusion summon allows you to dodge common targeting negates like Impermanence and Effect Veiler.
  • If Branded Lost is active, a fusion effect's activation cannot be negated. Many duelists neglect reading Branded Lost and often surrender when they waste a negate on a fusion summon! Cards that negate the activation like Baronne De Fleur, Borreload Savage Dragon, Tearlament Rulkallos and even Solemn Judgment cannot negate your Branded Fusion! Branded Lost is a perfect way to bait a negate or to guarantee your Fusion effect when you're against these threats.
  • If your Branded fusion was negated, the next best board you can make is double Masquerade the Blazing Dragon. After 5 actions, your opponent will run out of lifepoints to activate their effects!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

All the support for Branded over the last couple Masterduel packs creates a consistent, strong and resilient deck. Despite the semi-limit of the deck's crux - Branded Fusion, the deck is consistent and powerful enough to compete with the meta. Naturally playing through established boards while having a robust grind game is only something that few decks can boast, and now we have most of this support in Masterduel! To see for youself how this deck performs vs. meta, I highly recommend you see the deck in action by watching the Youtube video linked below!
 
Our hero, Albaz has faced his enemies to ultimately triumph through trials and adversity. Now, you can recreate the same experience as you pilot Branded all the way to Masters 1 in Masterduel ladder!

GLHF Duelists!

If we can win with OG Exodia, why not for another? Although you might say it's unnecessary, this deck is also a good example to teach you a turn skip trick with "Burning Bamboo Sword" + "Terminal World". Let's terminate our opponent with Exodius.

 

Gameplan

1) Have "Black Garden" plant 5 flowers. Then, destroy it with "Ancient Fairy Dragon".

2) Set "Diffusion Wave-Motion". This card will allow Exodius to attack all flowers to send all Exodia pieces to GY and win the duel. Better send Head of Exodia as last part for caution, just saying.

3) Convert the plants from Attack Position to Defense Position with "Earthquake". To be honest, after the clip, I actually noticed it's not necessary. Reason is that if you send Head of Exodia as the last part, Exodius won't attack last plant because by the time you have sent the last piece, you have already won thanks to meeting the win-condition of Exodius.

4) Bring forth first Exodius. Then, play "A Feather of the Phoenix" and target second Exodius to put that Exodius on top of your deck. It's needed so that if you have played "Into the Void" when you have Exodia pieces in your hand, you can reshuffle them back into the deck.

5) Meanwhile, we need to setup a turn skip trick:

  • First, play "Burning Bamboo Sword".
  • Then, "Broken Bamboo Sword", which pops up a question from Burning. Accept it to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1.
  • Afterwards, play "Terminal World".
  • If you watch the clip, you will notice that your opponent will jump straight from Main Phase 1 to Main Phase 2 to End Phase.

6) It's your turn now. Play second Exodius and target one of your Exodius with "Diffusion Wave-Motion".

7) Finally, attack into all flowers to win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Exodia the Forbidden One" can be found within "The Great Olds" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Diffusion Wave-Motion" can be found within "Legacy Pack" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 60 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_name: Dark World... but what if Danger! Monsters never existed?
deck_excerpt: 0 Danger! Monsters are in this deck. This deck only uses Dark World and other DARK/Fiend monsters. Extra/Side Decks are identical.
deck_description:
The main question of this deck is: What if Danger! Monsters were never introduced in Yu-Gi-Oh?

The point of this deck is to try and use ways to get around Special Summoning without any Danger! Monsters. As you have multiple ways getting around it (From the Underworld, Zalamander Catalyzer, Genta/Gates of Dark World, multiple draw cards, Dark Corridor), chances of running into a dead draw are unrealistic.

Because Dark World Monsters realy on them being discarded as an effect (and not a cost), Twin Twisters has been replaced with Solemn Judgment, and the Kaijus have been moved to main due to them being Fiends. Because of archetypes and Abyss Dwellers floating around the meta, Dark Ruler No More has been added back likewise into the Side. I like using Dark Ruler No More over Forbidden Droplet or Infinite Impermanence because you don't need to send any cards to your Graveyard and you don't have to think about immediately using the latter during your opponent's turn, and it's safer. Broww is also back into the deck for quickly drawing a card in a pinch.

Unfortunately, Dark World's biggest threats still remain Dimension Shifter and Droll & Lock Bird. Dark World does not like not having a Graveyard, much like how they don't appreciate having their deck searchers or draw power being shut down. However, Card Destruction and Dragged Down into the Grave have been added to get rid of your opponent's Droll & Lock Bird, albeit the former being a huge risk in case your opponent does draw into Droll. Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring can also negate Special Summoning Doomdog Octhros from the deck, although should you have a Triple Tactics Talent in your hand, you should be fine.

I obviously do not expect this deck to be taken seriously, but think of this more as an experiment than anything else. Whether you think it works or not is up to you. Just obviously as long as you don't see a Dimension Shifter or Droll & Lock Bird, you should be fine.

Blue-Eyes, -Eyes Dragon, LIGHT Monster, Seto Kaiba
deck_description: Trying to optimize Seto Kaiba's Blue-Eyes gimmick.

"Nouvelles" is a modern Ritual archetype that is based on chefs and French cuisine, as well as Michelin Stars. The archetypal Ritual Monsters have a Level between 1 and 6, the same amount of Michelin Stars there are, all of them are searchable with Preparation of Rites, and they all have effects to Tribute an Attack Position monster your opponent controls to summon another archetypal Ritual from your deck, usually with a higher Level, however, the low Level ones are trigger effects when a card os targeted for an effect or for an attack, and the high Level ones are ignition effects that become Spell Speed 2 if they were summoned by a Nouvelles monster. The Level 1 and 2 Rituals, Buerillabaisse de Nouvelles and Confiras de Nouvelles, are also written on their respective Ritual Spells, the "Recipes", so they are searchable with Pre-Preparation of Rites. Despite the monsters bring primarily comprised of Rituals, there are a couple of Normal Summons for the deck, as usual with Ritual-based decks, Diviner of the Herald is an excellent choice, in addition to the new Pendulum monster they will recieve in AGOV (Age of Overlord), Poissoniere de Nouvelles, which can add ANY Level 1 Ritual Monster or a Recipe card from your deck to your hand, can summon banish Recipe cards from your GY to summon a Nouvelles Ritual from your hand. If you control a Ritual Monster while Poissoniere is in your Pendulum Scale, you can target a monster on the field to change its position and special summon this card from the scale, which would trigger the low Level Nouvelles, and can also set itself back in the Pendulum Scale if it's Tributed, such as for a Ritual Summon.

They also have some powerful archetypal Spells and Traps. Their Field Spell, Nouvelles Restaurant "At Table", can add a Recipe from your deck to your hand when it's activated, can mulligan a Ritual Monster from your hand and draw a card, and can reset 2 cards from your GY, including a Recipe, and draw a card during your End Phase. Voici la Carte (Today's Menu) can help you search out your Nouvelles monsters, as well as add a Recipe from your deck or GY to your hand, based on what Type of monster you added. They also have 2 Ritual Spells, Recette de Poisson (Fish Recipe) and Recette de Viande (Meat Recipe), which have the same main effect to Ritual Summon, but have differing secondary effects, as Poisson adds a Recipe Ritual Spell from your deck or GY to your hand if it is used to Ritual Summon Buerillabaisse de Nouvelles, and Viande changes all monsters your opponent controls to Attack Position if it was used to summon Confiras de Nouvelles. Recette de Personnel (Staff Recipe) is a Continuous Trap that summons a token after you target a Ritual Monster you control, which would also trigger the low Level Nouvelles, and can Ritual Summon as a Quick Effect. And they also have a Counter Trap, Chef's Special Recipe, which can negate a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect if you control a Nouvelles Ritual Monster, and can destroy it if you Ritual Monster was summoned by the effect of a Nouvelles monster, and it also has a secondary effect, where if you summon Hungry Burger, you can Tribute your opponent's entire lineup of monsters.

Yes, that's right, this archetype supports everyone's favourite Warrior Ritual Monster (for whatever reason), Hungry Burger. This vanilla Ritual Monster from the early days of Yu-Gi-Oh recieved an archetype to call its home essentially 20 years after it came out. In addition to their new Pendulum monster coming in AGOV, they will also recieve Concours de Cuisine (Confectionery Contest), which is basically an archetypal Emergency Teleport that summons a Nouvelles Pendulum Monster and "Patissciel" Pendulum Monster from your hand, Deck, or Extra Deck, one to each field, as of right now, there is only a single target for each, the aforementioned Poissoniere, and the Fusion Monster Patissciel Couverture, additionally, it also has a GY effect which targets a monster on the field to have it gain a minor ATK boost, but the important part is that it targets, which can trigger the low Level Nouvelles. The only problem with this card is that it is unsearchable, however, you can use cards like Pot of Prosperity can help you find it, though this card can easy set up Turn 1 combos for the archetype. You can summon Poissoniere to your field and Patissciel to your opponent's, activate the effect of Poissoniere to search either a Ritual Monster or Spell, whichever you don't have, then Ritual Summon using Poissoniere and place it in your Pendulum Scale, and since you have a Ritual Monster and you gave your opponent a monster, you can activate the effect of Poissoniere in the scale to target a monster, to which you can activate the effect of a low Level Nouvelles to Tribute the Patissciel and summon another Ritual from your deck, finally giving the deck the comprehensive game plan and turn 1 strategy, which it sorely lacked on release, turning the deck from a slow, reaction-based deck, into an actually functional and somewhat competent archetype.

deck_excerpt: I made this out of spite because I saw a borderline unplayable list earlier.
deck_description:
*READ THIS BEFORE PLAYING AND/OR MAKING CHANGES*

So the deck is just a tool box for the extra deck. The extra deck can basically be anything you want, I just put generic stuff that I knew could be useful in there. 
You always want to try to get either an odd-eyes synchron or an odd-eyes valet out before using your normal summon to either go into synchro or xyz plays respectively.
If you use odd-eyes valet, you almost always want to send odd-eyes butler to your graveyard so you can activate odd-eyes butler's effect to go into some xyz hopefully plays.
If you activate the effect of celestial magician in your monster zone, you ALWAYS wanna take astrograph or odd-eyes dissolver.
If you activate wavering eyes ALWAYS grab monkeyboard or skullcrobat joker, then, depending on which you choose, use them to fetch each other unless you already have one of the two in hand.
If you start with a copy of guitartle in hand, ALWAYS activate it first in scale so you can get the draw effect; if the draw effect goes through chances are that opponents will ash it, or it will bait out a negate.
If you hate yourself, you can combo odd-eyes seer with valet by dumping something, then using seer's effect to special summon it out
Also, a friendly reminder that you only want to put stargazer in your pendulum scale if you have specifically celestial magician there.
*Odd-eyes pendulum dragon is there simply to give the deck some attack power but can definitely be removed

deck_excerpt: Use the P.U.N.K engine to get out massive beaters and recur your fiends endlessly.
deck_description:
The P.U.N.K engine is extremely synergistic with Archfiends, who are graveyard focused, have a lot of level 3s and 8s, and possess some strong recursion and backrow capabilities. Two of the centerpice monsters used by P.U.N.Ks, The Zombie Vampire and Psychic End Punisher, are also monsters Archfiends want to run for their gameplan, so the base gameplan for P.U.N.Ks also advances the Archfiend gameplan.

When going first, the ideal goal is to make Masterking and go through the P.U.N.K play sequence to make the Zombie Vampire and one or more of Chaos Angel, Baronne, and/or Hope Harbringer. Foxy Tune discards by effect, triggering Heiress and getting a boy on the board, the 600 LP cost of the psychic P.U.N.Ks allows Masterking to mill Tour Guide or Infernal Prodigy, and synergizes with the field spell, and tributing the Fusion can make A Deal With Dark Ruler live, enabling for Rank 8 plays. If you don't have the P.U.N.K pieces in your opening hand, you can still make a Chaos Angel if you have Infernal Prodigy + Archfiend Emperor/Diabolica, or if your Ze Amin gets Imperm'd/Ash'd, it and Garbage Lord can make Jam Dragon.

If you go 2nd, you want to aim for an OTK using Psychic End Punisher and/or Chaos Archfiend, but even Berserk Dragon can do the job. This is also where cards like Garbage Lord show additional utility, adding a body and making the OTK eaiser.

For fiends that you can mill for 600 LP, other good choices are Red Resonator, Sangan, or even Snipe Hunter, and Cherubini fits the deck as well.

deck_excerpt: turbo the gurgle then win brrrrr copium
Back with another Prediction Princess Deck
deck_description:
I may or may not have broken my left leg, but here is another Prediction Princess Deck which features Myutant this time around. With Myutant Synthesis is a Level 9 that is easily accessible through searching Myutant Fusion with Myutant ST-46 and Summoning a different Attributed Myutant from Deck with any of the small guys, targeting Synthesis with World Legacy Monstrosity gives you access to the Prediction Princess line with Mereologic Aggregator and also gives you options for further interruption such as a Monster, Spell, or Trap negate based on whichever Level 8 Myutant you have on field after your combo as well as a possible Myutant Cry into Synthesis or even Myutant Ultimus. 

For the Prediction Princesses, we are playing the usual 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse along with our choice of flips in 2 copies of Deus X-Krawler. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster face-up or face-down and Summons a Flip Monster from hand or GY during the End Phase. Tarotreith can be Ritualed or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect, but more importantly, it Summons a Flip Monster face-down from Deck when its flipped face-up and it can Quick Effect to flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse adds a Prediction Princess and a Ritual Spell from Deck on flip, it Summons itself back face-down if its Tributed, and it gives your Rituals targeting and destruction protection by your opponent's card effects. And Deus X prevents your opponent from activating monster effects on field after its been flipped with it being able to add a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than it when its destroyed. For the big Myutants, we are playing 1 each of Myutant Arsenal, Myutant Beast, and Myutant Mist. For the most part, these are just here to act as a different Attribute of Myutant you can search turn 1 to be able to make Synthesis with Myutant Fusion. However, if you do Summon them, and they remain on field, they are basically a negate for each card type. Beast negates a Spell Card or effect, Arsenal negates a monster effect, and Mist negates a Trap Card or effect. It is an interesting way to put up more interruption on your opponent's turn or in the case of Beast and Mist, a way to protect yourself against certain removal options, that being Spell or Trap-based removal. For the small Myutants, we are playing 3 Myutant ST-46, 2 Myutant M-05, and 3 Myutant Mutant. ST-46 searches a Spell/Trap on Summon, M-05 searches a monster on Summon, and Mutant can Special Summon itself from hand if you control a Myutant. These are all good effects to ensure you have access to Synthesis turn 1 for Monstrosity. However, I can't tell you how much I hate drawing just M-05 and no other Myutant. It is absolutely brutant searching a Myutant monster and sitting there with literally nothing to do (I mean nothing to do in this Deck and not in actual Myutant). Playing 2 gives you the option of getting another Attribute without having to use their Summon from Deck effect and goes well if you draw it and Mutant, but it just sucks to just draw it and nothing else. Each can Tribute themselves and banish a card from hand or face-up field (hand or Deck in the case of Mutant) to Special Summon a Myutant from Deck based on the card you banished. Monster gets you Beast, Spell gets you Mist, and Trap gets you Arsenal. This is how you would usually get the big Myutants on field for negates and for Fusion Material on your opponent's turn with Cry. And finally, the 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. There is an argument to play Greed Jar which can excavates the top cards of your Deck up to the number of cards your opponent controls and adds 1 to your hand, dumping the rest while also sending monsters from your Extra Deck to grave up to the number of monsters your opponent controls that were Special Summoned from the Extra Deck. For one, it adds any card you excavate which is really nice. Second, it can mill a high Level Myutant, giving you material for Ultimus on your opponent's turn if you have Cry set. Third, it can send copies of N'tss, Aggregator, and Garura or even Myutants from Extra for pops, negates, a draw, and giving you more material for an Ultimus, but it sort of conflicts with Tarotreith. You want to immediately do Tarotreith as quickly as possible to flip Deus X, but that also means that you would have to also flip Greed Jar as you would have no other way to do so on your opponent's turn afterwards. So it comes down to valuing Greed Jar or Deus X more, but I will always say that Deus X is just the better card overall in any situation. You have to wait for your opponent to amass something on their board for Greed Jar and waiting is not something you would like to do. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Myutant Fusion. This Fusion Summons a Myutant Fusion by banishing monsters from your hand and/or field as material, but if your opponent activated a card or effect this turn, you can also use up to 1 monster each from your Deck and GY as material. If you don't draw it, it is a great search off of ST-46, as you need access to Synthesis for a Level 9 to start your Prediction Princessing. You only need 1 copy as it is functionally dead in many situations if you don't have access to at least 2 Attributes of Myutant or if you draw multiple copies of it. 3 Emergency Teleport. It's not once per turn and it gets you any small Myutant from Deck which is absolutely great. It is functionally 3 extra ways to access any of your small Myutants. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Rituals a Prediction Princess from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can target Myutant Synthesis to get Bibliomuse and Deus X from Deck. Deus X and Synthesis can go into Aggregator who sends Herald for a Ritual search, you rinse and repeat by attaching back and Linking it off, and now you have access to all of your necessary Prediction Princess combo pieces. 1 Called by the Grave. 3 Myutant Cry which Fusion Summons a Myutant Fusion Monster during the Main Phase by shuffling monsters from field, grave or your face-up banished cards into the Deck. This gives you a a pop/partially unaffected body in Myutant Synthesis or a negate and banish in Myutant Ultimus. 

For the Extra Deck: 2 Myutant Ultimus which needs 3 Level 8 or higher Myutants and can negate the activation of a card or effect by banishing a Myutant card with the same type (monster, spell, trap) from your hand, grave, or face-up field, and banishes that card. If its destroyed by your opponent's card, you can add up to 3 of your banished Myutants, one each of a monster, spell, and trap. 3 Myutant Synthesis which needs 2 Myutants with different Attributes. On Fusion Summon, it can pop a card on the field and when your opponent activates a card or effect, you can make it unaffected by cards of the same type for the rest of the turn (monster, spell, trap). If it's destroyed by your opponent's card, you can add a banished Myutant to hand. This is the Level 9 you are making turn 1 to have a target for World Legacy Monstrosity. Sure, you have nothing to pop turn 1, but you are essentially putting a Level 9 on field which is important for your Prediction Princess plays while also putting a Level 8 or higher into rotation to make Ultimus on your opponent's turn with Cry. Or if you cannot make Ultimus, you can still make another Synthesis with Cry. 2 Herald of the Arc Light to send off of Aggregator for Ritual searches. 2 Mereologic Aggregator who can send a monster from Extra on Xyz Summon and it can also reattach monsters from GY which allows you to reattach Herald, giving you another Ritual search if you Link it off. 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows as a Rank 9 option. 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 S:P Little Night, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Cosmic Cyclone, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

If anyone has any advice on how to improve the deck please let me know. Thank you.

deck_excerpt: The Barrier Statue Lock is REAL!!!
deck_description: Marincess is arguably the deck with the cost-to-performance ratio in Yu-Gi-Oh! It has locks, removal and plenty of one-card combos. Combo guide available in the YouTube Video: https://youtu.be/dAppiZnwo-A
The strat is pretty simple - just fucking shed those life points bud

This deck is basically Skill Drain on CRACK! 

Watch it pop off here: https://youtu.be/SK7s45NCzaw

(Credit to DuelSphere for explaining the basics of Pendulums. Much appreciated!)

The universe is smiling upon you. D/D/D monsters are your best friends, which will grin with a devilish smile and send your opponent to Shadow Realm. Let's get cooking.

 

Gameplan

- Before we start, it would be for your benefit to read through what I call "Synchro Chain Train", where you can Synchro Summon monsters in a successive order to draw your deck...

1) If you open up with Monk >>> Panda, this is how you can play with...

  • Assuming that you have always spells to draw, this is how: Monk + Tuner = Librarian >>> Tuner + Non-Tuner = Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Martial >>> Martial brings Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Integrator >>> Martial + Integrator = Stardust >>> Stardust (Tuner due to Martial) + Non-Tuner = Ancient >>> Ancient pulls Level 1 Tuner >>> Ancient + Tuner = Accel >>> Accel pulls Level 1 Tuner >>> Accel + Tuner = Ravenous >>> Ravenous + Tuner = Nirvana
  • Assuming that there is a chance you might brick, this is how: Monk + (Tuner + Non-Tuner = Formula) = Stardust >>> Stardust + Tuner = Ancient >>> Ancient pulls Panda/Monk to continue the chain with Librarian and other Synchro monsters.

2) If you start only with Panda, this is how you can play with:

  • Tuner + Non-Tuner = Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Martial >>> Martial brings Formula >>> Formula + Non-Tuner = Integrator >>> Martial + Integrator = Stardust >>> Stardust (Tuner due to Martial) + Non-Tuner = Ancient >>> Ancient pulls Panda/Monk to continue the chain with Librarian and other Synchro monsters.

 

- Here is the evil plan:

1) Reach the situation as illustrated in those pictures below:

  • In those three pictures, I have showcased how to Pendulum Summon 2 x Armageddon. For those who don't know, I have placed Han-Shi on the left and Amazoness on the right. Han-Shi has a scale of 9 and Amazoness has a scale of 7. In between those numbers but not including 7 and 9, we can Pendulum Summon Armageddons. Reason is that between those scale numbers except themselves, we can Pendulum Summon monsters that fit Level wise. Armageddons are Level 8 monsters, so we have pulled them off out of hand no problem.
    • Monsters from hand has to be summoned in Main Monster Zones. In addition, if we had, let's say Blue-Eyes White Dragon (Level 8), we could also be able to Pendulum Summon it. So, Pendulum Summon isn't exactly exclusive to Pendulum typed monsters when pulled out of hand, as long as you meet the Level criteria and doesn't mention "Cannot be Special Summoned" in card text itself because Pendulum Summon is considered as Special Summoning. When you form the scales, you can just pull out monsters which fit between those scales level-wise.
    • If there were Pendulum Monsters placed face-up in Extra Deck, there would be two outcomes to also bring them forth alongside monsters pulled out of hand:
      • If there is no Link Monster, you have to place only one on "Extra Deck Zone".
      • If there are Link Monsters that point any Monster Zones, you can only place those face-up Pendulum Monsters to where arrows point to. I'm saying Link Monsters because in theory, there can be maximum two Link Monsters placed in a way that you can pull out at most four Pendulum Monsters placed as face-up in Extra Deck, which is what we will do to OTK with "Smile Universe".

 

2) Play "Polymerization" to bring forth "Purple Armageddon":

  • I need to clarify a thing or two regarding multiple types of Pendulum Monsters and other rulings:
    • You might say I could have used "Polymerization" without Pendulum Summon but if I did that, those Pendulum Monsters would have been sent to GY straight, instead of face-up Extra Deck like usual.
    • Although not in this deck, if you try to experiment with XYZ Pendulum Monsters, know that materials used for XYZ Pendulum Monster will be delivered to GY straight up. Whether they are Pendulum Monsters or not, anything within XYZ monster will go to GY. However, if XYZ Pendulum monster itself was either destroyed or used as Link material, it will go to Extra Deck as face-up. Give it a try with D/D/D Super Doom King Dark Armageddon, you will see what I mean.
      • Also, you can switch Level rule with Rank one for Pendulum Summoning explained in #1. As long as the monster in question has a Rank between the scale values except the values themselves, you can still bring XYZ Pendulum monster placed in Extra Deck as face-up but you have to obey the placement rules like usual.

 

3) Link Summon in a way that you can deliver "Purple Armageddon" and "Nirvana High Paladin" to Extra Deck as face-up:

  • Depending on the situation, you could also use "Baba Barber" but I used "Triple Burst Dragon".

 

4) Link Summon Saryuja by using Triple + Panda as Link materials to free up all of Main Monster Zones. Then, play "Monster Reborn" to place Triple as illustrated below:

  • Also, set "Smile Universe" and "Bad Reaction to Simochi". I think it's clear that we will convert healing into damage to OTK our opponent.

 

5) First, activate "Smile Universe". Then, "Bad Reaction to Simochi" to place all four Pendulum Monsters placed in Extra Deck as face-up to bring happiness to your opponent and yourself:

  • To activate all traps even during Draw Phase of your opponent, change "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch+Hold" and set to "ON" in-game. You can edit to "Switch+Hold" in "Duel" section of settings page.
  • You can watch the deck in action by clicking here!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played tutorial. What a good start to save up 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 510 SR and 60 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: No Maxx "C"? No Ash? Full Blackwing combo, bay-beeeee!!!!
deck_description:
A deceptively cheap deck for the upcoming Master Duel event. A majority of the cards for the deck can be attained by buying all three Blackwing Structure Decks for 1500 Gems, and if you own the staple Spells/Traps already (Dark Ruler, Triple Tactics, Called By, and Imperm), you only need to craft four URs (Draco Berserker, Nothung, Arc Rebellion, and Full Armor Master). There's a few SRs you might need to craft as well, like the Small Worlds and the Allure of Darknesses, but those are also mostly generic cards you can use in future decks.

Simoon is your main combo starter, you can use Small World to get it into your hand if you're lacking it (P.S, Radian is a bridge between all Blackwings that are in this deck), although Sudri can also get you to a solid endboard in a pinch. Only worry for deck during this event is Nibiru, which LIGHT team gets access to, but without Ash and the Roach, you'll likely get your combos off most of the time if going first. Raider's Knight/Arc Rebellion is a backup OTK if your opponent goes first and builds a powerful beatstick board that lacks the ability to negate that you can access if you got a combination of Sudri, Zephyros, or Shamal on the board

Summon the omni-negate Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon asap!

Hello everyone ,

I just wanted to share with you a fun decklist that I've been testing for a few days. It's pretty fun and quite good against decks Like Kash and purrely.

I don't feel like hand traps are necessary in this deck because the runick cards and spellbook of fate can pretty much deal with anything going second . Plus Jowgen is honestly a good card going second since he can wipe entire boards for a discard.

The bread and butter combo of this deck is Blue boi / secrets + any runick quick spell: will result in Utopic Draco Future + Jowgen + 3 spellbook card in hand at the end phase . Having another runick card will allow you to summon Sleipnir and draw 2 additional cards. if you managed to do that you're opponent will be stuck if he normal summoned to attack over jowgen , u either negate and steal or banish with Sleipnir.

And from there the deck can just bulid on that combo by activating more power spells like Nadir Servant and Runick spells to accumulate more advantage and draws

In case you got hit by Shifter or Droll u can instead of going into the UFD line u can go for Mannequin Cat target any of them and summon Jowgen from the deck  (since both shifter and Droll are spellcasters) and it should be enough to let you survive another turn since u can re summon jowgen back even if destroys it by battle because most likely droll or shifter is still on the field

Duality in this deck is honestly bonkers, Imagine tributing fleur delis after negating or Maximus (while dodging imperm eventually) to summon dragoon even if the manage to out it u can still recycle it back either with omega or grave effect of duality and draw 1.

The second target of duality is the fabled Unicore by tributing Geri which is really good since the runick cards allow you to control the amount of cards in ur hand on both players turns potentially turning any runick spell in ur hand into a solmen judgemnt with no cost (it's kinda gimmicky yes , but I managed to blow entire boards with unicore while letting my plays go through). Again if they manage to out it u just can recyle back just like dragoon.

The deck main focus isn't just to sit on Jowgen the entire duel. It's more like a way to turn 3 where it doesn't matter what ur opponent has on field u just have so much card avantage that u can deal with whatever the fuck they have on the board. And that is made easier by just the presence of UFD and the multiple ways u have to protect him ( Sleipnir , Spellbook of fate , Runick Slumber and Dogmatika punishement) or just summoning Winda just after they out Jowgen. But against some decks sometimes Jowgen is enough if Kash didn't draw the berth all their cards are basically dead and some decks like purrely and punk has no in-engine way to deal with it they just have to be skillfull at the game and draw the out.

 

Overall the deck does have flaws mainly evenly and Floowandereeze but I guess it's quite the same to all decks. The deck is simply fun and very rewarding if you play it right if u have any questions or suggestions I'm all ears.

deck_excerpt: Tired of cooking? Visit the nouvelles and get a tasty (and carnivorous) burger!!
first deck, Deck for attack and defense
deck_description: It is one of my first deck, I want to know your opinions and what are your deck defects

The deck revolves around getting out Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon as fast as possible and comboing into a couple different Xyz beatsticks that can run away with the game. Full-Armor is the optimal play if there are many Equip Spells onboard/in-hand, while Number C62 has some built-in protection. Overall this deck is very Xyz-based as well as having some counter-Xyz options and can pretty quickly get its boss monsters on the field, and keep reviving them if need be. It lacks a lot of utility in counters or negates, so the combos can be shut down with hand traps like Ash Blossom and Effect Veiler. D.D.R. enables monsters Banished by Photon Pirate or Monster Reborn Reborn to return; this also helps counter the effects of oponnent Banishing. The sheer number of Monsters in this deck and methods to get Xyz Monsters on the field can match up pretty well against negates, though, as decks that aren't loaded with negates and Traps may run out of ways to stop it. As a non-competitive deck, potential modifications to this deck could be SoRL to stall for a chance to draw needed cards, more negates for consistency, and a greater number of revival cards (CotH, etc). One could potentially modify this deck to synergize with Blue-Eyes, as a couple of the monsters' effects only specificy "LIGHT Dragon-type Monster" or "LIGHT Monster". Given the wealth of support Blue-Eyes has, this could be a lucrative option. The Side Deck just contains a couple monsters if the balance of high-low levels needs to be shifted, another disruptor (DMF) and 2 Fusion Spells if Fusion monsters match up well against the opponent. The Fusion pool for this deck is very limited (1) and there are no Synchros or Tuners, including this may be advantageous against similar decks to this one that have counter-Xyz cards. Overall I think the deck is built semi-well for a casual/starter deck and am excited to play with it once all the cards arrive.
