deck_excerpt: Does 3 Decatron and 1 Attondel make an Infernoid Deck?
deck_description:
Surely 3 Infernoid Decatron and 1 Infernoid Attondel make an Infernoid Deck. This is a bit of a wierd Deck. The strategy here is to Normal or Special Summon Infernoid Decatron in order to use its effect to send the Level 8 Infernoid Attondel from your Deck to the GY in order to make Decatron a Level 9, having it become a target on field for World Legacy Monstrosity. However, because you are essentially just playing 4 Infernoid monsters in the Main Deck to get you to a Level 9, there leaves a lot of space for non-engine as well as leaving you a lot of space in the Extra Deck to play pretty much anything you want. The only downside to this Deck is drawing the 1 Attondel you play as you cannot send from hand with Decatron.

Main Deck: Starting with the Infernoids, 3 Infernoid Decatron and 1 Infernoid Attondel. If Decatron is Normal or Special Summoned, you can send an Infernoid from your Deck to the grave in order to increase Decatron's Level by the Level of the sent monster and replace its name and effects with that monster's name and effects. Since we need to make Decatron a Level 9, we are going to be sending the Level 8 Attondel. Something to note about the Infernoids (excluding Decatron) is that they MUST be Special Summoned by their own effects and cannot be Special Summoned by other ways. There is a Level 9 Infernoid in Infernoid Devyaty, but since that Summoning requirement is slapped on it, we sadly cannot Monstrosity into it. Attondel requires you to banish 2 Infernoids from hand or grave to Summon it from hand or grave. It can attack twice if it destroys a monster by battle and can Tribute a monster to Quick Effect banish a card from your opponent's grave. Decatron inheriting Attondel's effect and it actually mattering rarely ever comes up, but either way, we are playing Attondel just to make Decatron a 9. For Prediction Princesses: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei flips a monster face-up or face-down as a Quick Effect and Summons a Flip Monster face-up or face-down from your hand or GY during the End Phase. Tarotreith can be Summoned by the End Phase effect of Tarotrei and when flipped, it can Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. Then, as a Quick Effect, it can flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse adds a Prediction Princess and a Ritual Spell from Deck when flipped, it can Summon itself back face-down if it's Tributed, and it gives your Ritual Monster targeting and destruction protection against your opponent's effects. Go go alongside these, we are playing 2 Deus X-Krawler, 3 Spirit of the Fall Wind, and 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. In the situation where you do not draw Decatron, you can use your Normal Summon on Spirit of the Fall Wind. When Spirit of the Fall Wind is Normal Summoned, it adds a Flip Monster from Deck to your hand. You may not see me playing it much in some other builds of Prediction Princess because it only triggers on Normal Summoning it, and most of my other builds of Prediction Princess have something you'd rather be using your Normal Summon on instead. However, Spirit is still an incredibly good card in Prediction Princess. It can add either Bibliomuse or Tarotreith to hand. In the case of Bibliomuse, it isn't searchable by anything in-archetype, so having a way to search it to have it in rotation for Ritual Summoning is very good. As for Tarotreith, having a piece of your Prediction Princess combo in hand early as possible means that you can focus on other plays later in the turn or not have to commit so much to adding pieces to your hand at a vital part in your combo, such as when you make Aggregator. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 One for One in order to get Decatron on field. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 2 Pre-Preparation of Rites. We have a lot of space in this Deck for other cards because our Infernoid part of the Deck is literally just 4 cards in addition to the One for One. In that case, we can play Pre-Prep to have a more consistent way of accessing Tarotrei and a Ritual Spell. 1 Triple Tactics Thrust and 2 Triple Tactics Talent as a way to continue your plays or at least try to prevent your opponent from starting their plays if you are interrupted during your turn. 1 Prediction Ritual and 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction. We are playing only the 1 Prediction Ritual as a search off of Pre-Prep. Having more than 1 copy in Deck means that you are basically boned if you draw 2 of it. Relying on Pre-Prep to get it from Deck gives you much more resources as it gets you both Prediction Ritual and Tarotrei. Underworld Ritual Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess from hand or GY face-up or face-down and can banish itself from GY during the Standby Phase to Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 1 Called by the Grave. 1 Crossout Designator. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity. 3 Infinite Impermanence. For the sake of Monstrosity, you could play another Level 9 in something like Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shinng Sky Stag or Pot of the Forbidden in order to be able to get 2 Level 9's from Deck if you target Tarotrei in a situation where you have your Ritual pieces but not Decatron. Void Feast is a very tempting card to play as it gets you Infernoids from Deck on your opponent's turn with one of them being Decatron as long as their Levels equal exactly 8 with Decatron being able to send something like Infernoid Devyaty or Infernoid Onuncu from Deck to copy its effect for a Monster or Spell/Trap negate. However, there are 2 issues with that. 1) You need to play Void cards other than Void Feast in order to meet its activation requirement of having to send a Void Spell/Trap from hand or face-up field to activate.There are no Void Spell/Traps that work well in this Deck. Into the Void is bad because you want to keep your cards and resources in hand and having to discard your entire hand is something you don't want to do. Void Apocalypse and Void Imagination functionally do nothing in this Deck. And Void Vanishment, while it is good as it can discard a card to add a Void Spell/Trap like Void Feast from Deck to hand, it locks you into Infernoids for the rest of the turn. Sure, you can activate it at the end of your combo to avoid that, but it brings us to our next issue with Feast. 2) You need to play more Infernoids. Infernoids have to be Special Summoned by their own effect. And while Void Feast ignores those conditions, you are stuck with monsters that you literally cannot do anything with if you draw them. Maybe playing 1 more Infernoid name in Onuncu or Devyaty is fine in order to have access to a Spell/Trap or monster negate, but playing more names that don't do anything on their own and are not able to hard summon in this Deck will only make the Deck more bricky.

For the Extra Deck: 1 Baronne de Fleur. If you didn't know that Decatron is a Tuner, now you know. If you already have access to your Prediction Princess combo, or if you have another way to access Decatron like One for One, you can use it as a Level 1 Tuner to go into Baronne. Another Level 10 Synchro you could play is Masterflare Hyperion which can send something like The Executor of the Underoworld - Pluto or Protector of the Agents - Moon to copy their effect for a book or pop. And it can also banish a Fairy from hand or GY when your opponent activates a card or effect to banish a card on field. 2 Herald of the Arc Light for Ritual searches when sent with Aggregator. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 Stellar Nemesis T-PHON - Doomsday Star, and 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck on Xyz Summon and can also reattach a monster from GY. You can send Herald for a Ritual search, reattach it, and Link off Aggregator for another search. 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World, 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

For the Side Deck: 1 Infernoid Devyaty and 1 Infernoid Onuncu. If you really wanted to, you could side 1 of them in to allow Decatron to send it and copy its effects for a Monster negate or a Spell/Trap negate. It's not exactly optimal, but it is definitely something you could do. 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Cosmic Cyclone, and 3 Evenly Matched.
I'm planning on buying this deck soon maybe.

deck_description: Gaia + Black luster fun for casual games between old school and "actual"

This deck outpermormed my expectations with a win streak of 31 from d5 to master1, not an easy deck tho you have a lot of options and it can get confusing.

Just remember always go second, if you want to go first you gonna need the 3 cards on the side deck to summon the fossil dyna on opponent turn.

As for the side deck I never play the savage dragon, masquerena, Donner; those 3 cards are irrelevant since you end almost every duel before turn 3,  also the Accescode Talker only saw play on 3 or 4 games total not super important but it did save me once, I go appollousa into borrelsword or borrelsword into appollousa almost every game right after breaking the board with the golems and beyond the pendulum/duster/dark hole, the maxx c on turn 1 always on stand by phase to benefit from kashtira.

The only real threat is a good tearlaments player, the matchup of Vaylantz vs Tearlaments is super technical and will test your knowlege of the game

tips:

*leave 1 monster alive for the borrelsword dmg increase

*Beyond the pendulum is not once per turn, if you get impermed or ashed just get the second one online

*you can play mind games with your opponent with the saion throwing coins

*Dominator denies 1 set card and steals 1 monster to use for fodder

*The Grand Duke only does dmg when the card returns to hand not when they return to extra deck

*When you summon gamma on your turn just use both pieces for a free beyond the pendulum with the help of link spider, seriously the savage dragon is just a place holder on this deck

*A mosnter stolen with Dominator that is lvl 6 or above can be turned into Grand Duke

*Always get the Grand Duke out before the link 4 summon in order to bring the Grand duke back with the Viscount second ability 

*Check GY before the pot of desires to check if you need to summon something before the pot, that pot has been really good on this deck I only lost my combo on the banish 1 game out of 50
Once speeder resolves it's combo after combo

Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Tyler Robert Weathers

Tournament: Hollywood WCQ Regional - August 13th 2023

Hello there! Today, I learned that "Independent Nightingale" was actually used alongside "Supreme King Dragon Starving Venom" to copycat Nightingale and unload a big damage in higher competitive matches with Pendulum decks in mind, which looks viable. Rather than relying on her OG ability, which is done right there, I wanted to give a shot by copycatting Nightingale with Venom before the probability of banning Venom happens in MD. Venom is banned in TCG but not in OCG, so I'm not sure what will happen to this fella in MD. Let's jump right into the action.

 

(This is a hungry and venomous Nightingale! Be cautious!)

 

Gameplan

1) Play first "Polymerization" to bring forth Nightingale. "Independent Nightingale = Warbler + Assembled" is your equation. You can trigger Nightingale or not, doesn't matter. Reason is that there will be infinite turn skip trick with Arcana and you can copycat Nightingale with Venom and trigger Venom, instead.

2) Play second "Polymerization" to bring forth Venom. "Venom = Zero + Infinity" is your equation. When Nightingale is present on the battlefield, you can copycat Nightingale and trigger Venom to deal 4000 damage per turn.

3) Place "Light Barrier" and Link Summon "Saryuja" to bring forth Arcana. Pick heads to always skip your opponent's turn at the cost of two of your monsters on the battlefield. Sabres + Balerdroch will be the ones and they will come back forever. Thus, you can take as many turns as you like.

4) Deal 4000 damage repeateadly until your opponent is dead by targeting Nightingale with Venom and activating Venom.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Arcana" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Doomking Balerdroch" can be found within "Abyssal Underworld" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Independent Nightingale" + "Assembled Nightingale" can be found within "Moonlit Avian Dance" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Supreme King Dragon Starving Venom" can be found within "Indomitable Knights" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 570 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Turbo out the Gate Guardian fusion monsters.
deck_description:
The deck focuses turboing out the "Gate Guardian" fusion monsters. Use Labyrinth Heavy Tank, Elemental HERO Prisma, Labyrinth Wall Shadow (field spell), Fusion Armament, and Fusion Deployment to get a Sanga of the Thunder, Suijin, and Kazejin on the field, and then special summon your choice of fusion monster(s). You can search the field spell with Terraforming or by discarding Shadow Ghoul of the Labyrinth. You can recover your field spell from the GY with Barricadeborg Blocker. Gate Guardians Combined can use materials from your hand, field, and GY, so use Foolish Burial, Hand Destruction, and Elemental HERO Prisma to get Sanga of the Thunder, Suijin, and/or Kazejin in the GY. This helps extend your plays while setting up for it. Most of the Gate Guardian support cards allow you recycle your Sanga of the Thunder, Suijin, and Kazejin so you can go into another "Gate Guardian" fusion monster. 

Double Attack! Wind and Thunder!!, Prey of the Jirai Gumo, Knightmare Phoenix, and Knightmare Unicorn are additional removal options. For difficult to remove cards, you can use your level 9 fusion monsters to Xyz summon into Laevatein, Generaider Boss of Shadows. Then immediately tribute it (effect) to summon Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity, and attach those problem cards to it as material. Then you can follow-up with Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.

The deck is meant for casual play; however, you can consider swapping out Fusion Reserve, Hand Destruction, and Riryoku Guardian for your own staples, hand traps, and tech choices.

People really need to play this deck more!

Watch it pop off here: https://youtu.be/5gXfJj-y_V0

deck_excerpt: Make use of Revolution Synchron and Visas Amritara for a vastly stronger Tearlaments strategy!
deck_description:
Post Duelist Nexus, Tearlaments receives two new toys that vastly boost its consistency - Revolution Synchron and Amritara. Revolution Synchron coupled with Ancient Fairy Dragon (often known as AFD) searches a field spell if one is already set-up on the field - such as Perlereino. More importantly, Revolution Synchron summoned from GY + AFD summons Visas Amritara. Amritara then searches out a missing Tearlaments spell/trap! Further on as you play, Amritara can destroy a Tearlament monster of yours on the field to trigger your GY effect, further extended your plays. The Sychron package also mills cards from deck. Both Tuning and Revolution Synchron mill one card each! 
 
On top of the usual powerful tools already in the Tearlament arsenal, access to any spell or trap through Visas Amritara in Tearlaments vastly improves the consistency of this deck. More consistency means more mills, more effects, more fusions and more wins! The triple synergy between Revolution Synchron, Ancient Fairy Dragon and Visas Amritara give Tearlaments a much needed power boost - perhaps to Tier 1 status once again! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 

 

Forming the core of this strategy, the Tearlament portion of this deck consists of 20 cards. 3 Perlereino and 1 Terraforming allow you to search for the 9 maindeck Tearlament monsters, Scheiren, Havnis, Merrli, 3 Reinoheart and 3 Tearlaments Kashtira. 3 Scream, 2 Sulliek, 1 Heartbeat and 1 Grief search/recur for additional cards when milled. 

 

A Synchron package is used, composed of 2 Revolution Synchrons and 3 Tuning so enable the summon of Visas Amritra and mill some cards. 

 

A mini Kashtira package of 1 Wraithsoth (often the search target for AFD) and 3 Kashtira Tearlaments. 

 

1 of each Ishizu fairy are used since they are mill enablers and GY shufflers. They are all perfect discards/fusion material. Kelbek also functions as a decent handtrap.

 

3 King of the Swamp and 1 Polymerization as a search target is included, since they function as specific names when used for fusion material in the GY when fusing with Tearlaments. This gives you access to strong fusion monsters like Rulkallos and Grapha. Polymerization is also deceptively strong because nobody really negates it, and since it presents 1 pop, 2 draw with a 3300/3300 untargetable body with Guardian Chimera. 

 

6 boardbreakers are present in the form of Gameciel (an aqua type, which is useful fusion material for Kaleido-Heart) and Super Polymerization. 

 

You may have noticed that there are hardly any handtraps or generic staples in this deck. The theory behind this build of Tearlaments is that it has so much gas that it can play through all of your opponent's interruptions just fine, as long as your graveyard is accessible and you aren't floodgated to death.

 

40 cards are used to ensure this strategy is as consistent and compact as possible. In addition to bricking less, the mills will have much better results than bigger Tearlaments variants because of the deck's compact size. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 

 

Tearlaments' gameplan is to mill as much as possible to trigger Tearlament effects. Tearlament monsters are ideal to mill as much as possible to turbo out powerful fusion monsters like Grapha and Rulkallos to protect your combo lines. Like every Tearlaments strategy, this deck aims to mill as much as possible and gain beneficial effects from those mills. The reliance on mills makes this strategy unpredictable and luck dependant, meaning that there are hardly any straightforward combos. Combos are hand/mill dependent - leaving the rest of the game up to the duelists individual skill, decision making and mental fortitude (that's the Tearlaments is regarded as a difficult to pilot deck). Tearlaments are also infamous for requiring a great deal of skill, since the pilot has to be aware of the various interactions they have in the GY and the amount of cards left in their maindeck. 

 

First, you do as much milling as possible to get searches triggered and your GY set-up. Your boards vary, but generally have a mix of Rulkallo's summon negate, Grapha's omni-negate, Kaleido-Heart's shuffle, Sulliek's negate, Perlereino's pop and Ishizu card's graveyard shuffling. 

 

Going second, this deck's gas ploughs through interruption and negates (especially if you chainblocked to guarantee effects to go through). Boards are also cracked open with Super Polymerization, Gameciel, and Guardian Chimera. 

 

 

Here is the deck's new fancy combo featuring Ancient Fairy Dragon, Revolution Synchron and Visas Amritara:
 
Level 4 monster + Revolution Synchron = Field spell search, +1000 LP gain, Tearlament spell/trap search. 
  1. Do your opening plays to search and mill to set up your GY. 
  2. Normal summon your level 4 monster. If it has an effect, activate the effect. 
  3. Synchro summon Ancient Fairy Dragon (AFD) using a Level 4 monster + Revolution Synchron. 
  4. If there is a field spell on the board, activate AFD's effect to gain 1000 LP and search a fieldspell from deck. 
  5. Special summon Revolution Synchron from the GY with it' effect and mill 1 card.
  6. Synchro summon Visas Amritara using AFD + Revolution Synchron (now a level 1). 
  7. Activate Visas Amritara's on-summon effect to search for a needed Tearlaments Spell/Trap. 
  8. Keep milling and fusing in the GY until you resolved all effects and your field is full of fusion monsters!

 

GENERAL TIPS

 

  • Mill as much as possible when before fusion summoning so you have as much options in the GY as fusion material as possible. If you milled King of the Swamps and Tearlament girls, you've hit a home run since they fusion summon Grapha or Rulkallos!
  • Visas Amritara can trigger your Tearlaments monsters GY effects by destroying them on the field. For example, Amritara destroys Kaleido-Heart on the field -> Kaleido-Heart summons itself from GY and sends Tear girl to GY -> tear girl fusion summons using materials from GY. Amritara allows for additional extension!
  • Branded Tearlaments lacks in-engine ways to remove backrow, except with Guardian Chimera. Backrow floodgates absolutely slaughter this strategy, so if you're against an opponent using something like Rivalry of Warlords, it probably is time to proceed to next game! Be sure to side in backrow hate in those match-ups!
  •  Guardian Chimera is the best card to crack open established boards. With it's untargetability, beefy 3300ATK/DEF statline and non-targeting destruction, and its effect chainblocked by other monsters after fusion summon, most boards fall to this offensive juggernaut. If your opponent negates Polymerization to prevent Chimera from coming out, they have wasted a precious interaction paving the way to  milling cards. 
  • When siding out for games, my favourite cards to side out are the boardbreaking cards (Gameciel and Superpoly) for more appropriate cards. 3 more slots for siding out are available at the expense of this deck's consistency - I would take out 1 Revolution Synchron, 1 Tearlaments Heartbeat and 1 Tearlaments Scream. That's a grand total of 9 slots sidedeck slots.
  • Any Tearlaments strategy is infamous for requiring a great deal of skill to pilot, since the duelists is required to know all the various interactions that goes on in the GY, and to remember how many cards are left in their deck - the while considering how the opponent will react to the plays. This deck is not easy, so practice makes perfect with Tearlaments. 
     
    Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING REMARKS

 

When Visas Amritara was released, I thought the card was the coolest design ever. The guy's big buster blade reminds me of Cloud from Final Fantasy 7 or Guts from Berserk! Revolution Synchron's design charmed me as well - he is a cute lil' chibi grasshopper looking mfer based on Powertool Dragon. Imagine my delight when I discovered they can work together in a favourite deck of mine! Using a level 4 to synchro summon, field spell searching, destroying your own monsters on field to trigger effects - the synergy of Revolution Synchron, Visas Amritara and AFD is incredible! It's like Konami purposely released all of them at the same time so we can use it like this! 
 
I personally still find the Tearlaments playstyle quite fun - the randomness of the mills and the dopamine hit when the mills actually succeed feel so goooood! I like how this deck actually requires skill - it rewards the pilot's decision making, resource management and situational awareness. I personally find it so badass and satisfying pulling everything off! 
 
Tearlaments is the posterchild of archetypes "suffering from success" as they've had all their good cards and starters banned (RIP Chaos Ruler) or limited to 1 (Rest in PISS Ishizu cards). COPIUM, dedication and creativity are the only things keeping Tearlaments players alive in this day and age - and now that is demonstrated with the new support post-DUNE! Perhaps now Tearlaments can start topping again with this excellent support. 

 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_description:
Allow me to tell you the tale of how this deck came to be. I was sitting in my room when suddenly, I had a thought. "I feel like playing timelords." So I made a timelord deck. It sucked. I thought, "hmm.. How can I make this less garbage?" Then, I remembered Savage Colosseum existed. So, I decided to add it, along with a crap ton of cards to search it. Now, we have a neat gimmick deck. But, it still sucks. So I decided, "I'm gonna add some stupid powerful cards into this." So I added Pot of Extravagance and Summon Limit. The deck still isn't great. But if you REALLY want to you can play it I guess. I'm gonna spend the next while trying to improve this deck, so check back every once in a while, because I may have changed the deck.

 

Wait how to play the deck? Just get Savage Colosseum on the field along with some timelords. If you can get Infinite Light along with Summon Limit you're pretty much set for life. If your opponent has spell/trap removal, go to your local church and pray the don't draw it. Also if you're fighting a deck with a consistent way to get rid of your timelords, you can employ the strategy of getting up and leaving.

deck_excerpt: Crazy deck with lots of one-ofs and creative lines. (Guide included)
deck_description:
Main Line

So the main line is quite simple actually. It's a classic  Normal summon + Steal some monster -> Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy or another Link-2 Charmer -> Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians -> Accesscode Talker 

The thing is, since the deck has ~30 unique cards, there are tons of ways of getting there. 

General tips

1. You probably want to go second. The thing is you need material for your summons. If they don't put anything in play you will need 3 summons to do the main line, and you want to hit right away with Talker or Lethal. The deck is capable of doing it, but there is not much value for you on the first turn.
2. You can play first if you are running Secret Village of the Spellcasters and/or Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin to set up the lock, but that's your choice.
3. People won't probably know you are running this cocktail, surprise them.
4. Some boards can get nasty with attribute variety and Awakening of the Possessed. So keep in mind you may just summon a bunch of monsters and swing for lethal.

Individual Card Tips

Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage! 
1 Play Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage! -> Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones or Lightning Storm  FIRST. Just something to remember, as you have to play them on an empty board.
2. From Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones you can Sky Striker Ace - Kagari -> Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones and go back to charmers line with DARK, FIRE, or Sky Striker Ace - Shizuku for WATER.

Spirit Charmers  
1. Play Spirit Charmers LAST, even if you have Called by the Grave. If you get that Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring'd you get 2x1'd. You can recover but that's not good. Always bait with something else. Also, clever players may hold on to it.
2. Remember you can add the spell/trap card to your hand and set the monster. 

Called by the Grave 
1. Try to Called by the Grave a Maxx "C". If they had 2, then tough luck.
2. Don't banish Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring if they don't target Spirit Charmers! Eat that one up. Target Maxx "C", else you'll make them draw tons and you don't have the steam to deck them out.  

Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden 
1. Works as a wildcard to turn any of your Spellcasters into a LIGHT attribute monster try not to spend it early.
2. Try to summon her before going for an Accesscode Talker so you can get more material for it.

Dotscaper 
1. Try to discard it or bury it. Use One for One, Spirit Charmers, Foolish Burial or Fateful Adventure 
2. You can turn it into a Relinquished Anima resummon it and go for DARK, EARTH, or LIGHT (with Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden) charmer right after.

Foolish Burial 
1. Targets: Dotscaper, Water Enchantress of the Temple, Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous(if you fusion summoned). Also, Jigabyte if you have a Ranryu.

Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon 
1. Targets: Sanwitch, Rite of Aramesir, Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones 

Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians 
1. It's a quick effect. So hold on to your spell counters and quick-summon a Fairy Tail - Luna. Also lets you draw for Awakening of the Possessed on your opponent's turn. 
2. Remember you need a spellcaster to get her out. You will probably get to her through Link-2 Charmers but the cards on the deck ensure you have enough spellcasters even if you don't steal with your charmer and have to go a different route. 

Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous 
1. Remember to get her back at EOT if you ditched your Thousand-Eyes Restrict or Sanwitch.
2. Another reason to go 2nd.

Sky Striker Mecha - Widow Anchor, Change of Heart, Mind Control, Monster Reborn
1. Sort of the bread and butter. They act as removal and net you a Link-2 charmer you can use to get the monster you stole from them back from their GY, which turns into Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians, etc...

Deckbuilding / Alternatives

Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians 
1. Run two just because you can hold for a turn with a Fairy Tail - Luna 

Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin 
1. If you run this, you may want to add Terraforming, Metaverse, and Secret Village of the Spellcasters. 
2. Also, drop your charmers and add Familiar-Possessed - Wynn, so you enable discarding her for a Ranryu.

Sanwitch vs Kamionwizard 
1. Sanwitch is dark and a spellcaster so you can pop it into Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden. It is probably better if you want to summon it with Selene, which won't probably happen.
2. Kamionwizard. You can get it in with either Ready Fusion or Instant Fusion. 

The main deck familiar-possessed are interchangeable. They are in for Attribute coverage, but you can swap them out for whatever you need.

The side deck is just maybes, not a real sideboard.

Cards like Imsety, Glory of Horus, Pharaonic Sarcophagus, Diabellestarr the Dark Witch, snd Magicians' Souls all send cards from your hand to gain you advantage in one way or another, like how Diabellestarr summons itself and gives you access to "The Sinister Spoils" Spell/Traps, or how Souls sends Spells or Traps to draw you cards. Overall, this deck is very consistent, and extremely flexible and fun, enjoy.

deck_excerpt: Not completely sure about this one
deck_description:
On a scale between Cryston Prediction Princess (0) to Rescue-ACE Prediction Princess (10), I'd have to give Amazoness Prediction Princess like a 2 or 3. There is 1 upside to the 2 downsides of playing Amazoness as a way to get a Level 9 out on the field for Prediction Princess. The 1 upside is that Amazoness Princess is a 1-card Level 9 in Amazoness Pet Liger King.The 2 downsides are that 1) Amazoness Pet Liger King is an EARTH monster which means we have to play more non-EARTH Level 9's in your Main Deck to actually have targets for World Legacy Monstrosity that are actually Summonable off of targeting Liger King. It may not seem like too much of an issue until you realize that you cannot get Prediction Princess Bibliomuse out of the Deck with Monstrosity due to it and Liger both being EARTH monsters. 2) Why is Amazoness Call a Quick-Play Spell? If it wasn't, then either Amazoness Princess or Amazoness War Chief by themselves is a 1-card Level 9 on field. Since you are setting an Amazoness Spell/Trap or Poly from Deck with War Chief, you cannot activate Call because it's a Quick-Play and you can't activate Quick-Plays the turn they are set. Either way, here's the Deck.

Starting with the Amazoness monsters, 3 Amazoness War Chief and 3 Amazoness Princess. War Chief can be Specialed from hand if you have no monsters or if you control only Amazoness monsters. And if its Normal or Special Summoned, you can set a Poly or Amazoness Spell/Trap from your Deck. This card is your Poly searcher and it cannot be Ashed since it sets instead of adding which is nice. But again, the fact that you cannot actiate Amazoness Call after setting it with War Chief due to it being a Quick-Play Spell makes this Deck so much worse than it already is. If it wasn't a Quick-Play, you could activate it to search Princess, Normal Princess, add Secret Arts, and still have a 1-card combo for a Level 9 on board. But that just isn't the case. Princess is treated as Amazoness Queen on field or in GY which is useful if you want to play Amazoness Empress (if you really wanted to even though it doesn't do anything). On Normal or Special, it adds an Amazoness Spell/Trap from Deck to hand. You usually will be searching Amazoness Call in order to use it to search for War Chief, Summoning the War Chief from hand, setting Poly from Deck, and making Pet Liger King with Princess and War Chief. If you already have War Chief in hand, you can also choose to add Amazoness Secret Arts which is their Fusion Spell with the War Chief in hand setting something like Call to search for resources for next turn. We are not playing any other Amazoness monsters for several reasons. 1) This is not an "Amazoness" Deck. Playing too many names that don't help you go into Pet Liger King is redundant. 2) The Pendulums functionally do nothing in a non-dedicated Amazoness Deck. 3) While Amazoness Spiritualist is somewhat of a nice card, it only triggers off of Special Summon to add a Poly, and its own effect to Summon itself restricts you into Amazoness monster from the Extra Deck which is not what we want. For Prediction Princesses: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei Summons a Flip from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase and it can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down. Tarotreith can be Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On flip, it can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and as a Quick Effect, it can flip any number of monsters you control face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse adds a Prediction Princess and Ritual Spell from Deck on flip, it can Summon itself back face-down when Tributed, and it gives you Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection against your opponent's card effects. We are only playing 1 Deus X-Krawler as we cannot Special Summon it off of World Legacy Monstrosity targeting Pet Liger King. Having the 1 to Summon off of Tarotreith is enough in that case. For our other Level 9's, we are playing 1 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Knightmare Incarnation Idlee, and 3 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag. Thunder King is pretty much just a Level 9 target in this instance. Idlee is a strange one because if you Summon her off of Monstrosity, she can actually prevent the monsters you Summoned off of Monstrosity from being destroyed during the End Phase in addition to all of your Level 9's in general. It's effect to send all Links on field to the GY on Special Summon if yur opponent controls more Links than you rarely comes up. Kaku is basically a free Summon from hand when there is a monster in the EMZ. For one, it is summonable off of Monstrosity, but if you do draw it, you can make Pet Liger King in the EMZ to Summon Kaku from hand to go into Aggregator even without the help of Monstrosity which is really nice. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Reinforcement of the Army as your 4th copy of Amazoness Princess. 1 Amazoness Secret Arts which Fusion Summons an Amazoness Fusion using monsters from your hand or field, and you can banish it from GY to be able to send an Amazoness from your Extra Deck for a Fusion Summon during that turn once. It is searchable off of Princess, making it a good card to at the very least run if you already drew War Chief and don't need to search for Call. Speaking of, 3 Amazoness Call which is a Quick-Play Spell for some reason, but more importantly, it can either add or send an Amazoness from Deck. Drawing this card alone and no other Amazoness monster basically means that you cannot access your Amazoness plays sadly. That's because Princess only adds an Amazoness Spell/Trap and Call is a hard OPT. You usually search it off of Princess, but drawing it and at least 1 Amazoness name gets you to Pet Liger King. And of course, there is the stipulation of it being a Quick-Play, making it bad with War Chief setting an Amazoness Spell/Trap from Deck. 1 Polymerization to set off of War Chief. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity. 2 Pre-Preparation of Rites to search both Tarotrei and the 1 Prediction Ritual we play. Because of Call being a Quick-Play, you are very often left with no ways to access a Level 9 as 1/2 of Aggregator if you draw just it or War Chief. In that case, we need more ways to access our Prediction Princess cards. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction. 3 Pot of Prosperity, and 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 2 Amazoness Pet Liger King which needs a Level 5 or higher Amazoness and another Amazoness monster. Functionally, it doesn't do much in this Deck other than it being a Level 9 that is easily Summonable for Rank 9 Material and as a target for Monstrosity on field. I guess that if it does stick on field or if you bring it back with Nine-Lives Cat, it does prevent your opponent from attacking your other monsters which is something at the very least. 2 Herald of the Arc Light for Ritual searches off of Aggregator. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer which pops cards equal to the number of materials you detach from it, and it can attach anything it runs over, giving you a 2 material Zeus after the Battle Phase. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck on Xyz Summon, it can detach any number of materials to reattach the same number of monsters in the GY to itself, and if you send Herald for a Ritual search and reattach it, Linking off Aggregator, you get another Ritual search. 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows. 1 Nine-Lives Cat, 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 S:P Little Night, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

For the Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 2 Lightning Storm, 3 Cosmic Cyclone, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: We out here hard summoning N'tss in Prediction Princess
deck_description:
Even though Virtual World is a good Level/Rank 9 engine, I didn't think too much about it in terms of a Prediction Princess Deck. You can't Summon Link Monsters in Virtual World which means that you wouldn't be able to Link off Aggregator to send Herald to the grave again. But hear me out: Elder Entity N'tss is can be Specialed by sending a Synchro and an Xyz to the grave. Virtual World is a Synchro and Xyz Deck, and it is incredibly easy to get both Synchros and Xyz Monsters out on the field and get them back from the graveyard, especially with cards like Cloudcastle and Nine-Lives Cat. You have so much more options in this Deck as opposed to some other builds of Prediction Princess. While it is a shame you cannot play Number F0: Utopic Draco Future instead of N'tss due to the Virtual World restriction, you still very much have the option of playing Virtual World, playing Prediction Princess, or doing both. Sure, it still has the Virtual World issue of not drawing enough names in your starting hand, an issue that is further increased with Ritual cards in the Deck, it is still a very neat Deck that does its plays well if you know how to play Virtual World optimally.

Every Virtual World (other than Nyannyan) has the effect to target a face-up Virtual World card you control while in hand, send a Virtual World card from your Deck to the grave with a different card type than the targeted card to Special Summon itself, and each of them have a bonus effect if you do so. We are playing 1 Virutal World Hime - Nyannyan, 3 Virtual World Mai-Hime - Lulu, 3 Virtual World Xiezhi - Jiji, 3 Virtual World Roshi - Laolao, and 2 Virtual World Kirin - Lili. Nyannyan can Summon itself from grave as a Tuner if you summon a Level 3, but it's banished when it leaves the field, and if it's banished, it can shuffle back a banished card. Lulu adds a Virtual World card of the 3rd card type that you did not target or send from Deck. Jiji adds back a Virutal World monster from grave during the End Phase its Special Summoned by its own effect. Laolao Summons back a Virtual World monster from grave with its effects negated. And Lili sends a Virtual World card of the 3rd card type that you did not target or send from Deck. Nyannyan is a great extender. Lulu is the searcher. Jiji is a name and a Level 3. Laolao gets back a Tuner or non-Tuner of the Level you need. Lili I guess can dump Nyannyan, Qinglong, or Xuanwu. You can't summon monsters for the rest of the turn except for Level/Rank 3 or higher monsters if you use their effects which means you can't play Links which is why we are using N'tss to get Aggregator off the field. For the Prediction Princesses, it is the usual 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, and the 2 Deus X-Krawler. Tarotrei summons a Flip from hand or grave during your End Phase and can Quick Effect flip a monster face-up or face-down. Tarotreith can be Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect, it Summons a Flip face-down from Deck on flip, and it can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse adds a Prediction Princess and a Ritual Spell from Deck on flip, it can Summon itself back if its Tributed, and it gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection against your opponent's effects. Something good about the Prediction Princess Ritual Monsters, Tarotrei and Tarotreith, is that you can Ritual Summon from graveyard with Underworld Ritual of Prediction, and for Tarotreith, you can either Ritual it from grave or you can use Tarotrei to Summon it face-down from grave during the End Phase. Qinglong and Xuanwu both require you to discard a card after their effect resolves, so not having to worry about keeping your Ritual Monsters in hand is nice in terms of keeping resources and still having plays.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Virtual World City - Kauwloon which places a Virtual World Gate from your Deck face-up in your Spell/Trap Zone. Don't really care much about its additional effects because you rarely get to the ones that matter in this Deck and in Virtual World itself. 1 Harpie's Feather Duster which is realistically the 40th card in here. You can side it, but I wouldn't know what to MainDeck pre-side otherwise as your 40th card. 2 Virtual World Gate - Qinglong which banishes a Virtual World from grave to negate the effects of a face-up monster on the field until the End Phase, but the more important of its effects if banishing it to search a Virtual World and send a card from hand. It gets you to more names and can easily be sent from Deck to summon any of them which is good. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction. This Rituals from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it during the Standby Phase to Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 1 Called by the Grave. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity. It is not completely necessary to have this card in your hand for your Prediction Princess plays, but it does really help with getting Bibliomuse into rotation and for putting more material on field, specifically to make a Rank 9 like Nine-Lives Cat to get back a Level 9 (Synchro or not) to either keep extending in the direction of another Rank 9 in Laevateinn or put a Synchro on field to send it and Aggregator for N'tss to get Herald into the grave again for another search. 3 Emergency Teleport which is not OPT, so it's great for getting a Tuner or non-Tuner on field or into rotation, being the case for Nyannyan. 2 Virtual World Gate - Chuche which shuffles 2 banished Virtual World cards with different names into the Deck to pop a face-up card on the field. You can also banish it from grave during your End Phase to increase or decrease the Level of a Virutal World you control by 3. 1 Virtual World Gate - Xuanwu which is here to send from Deck in order to banish it to Special back a Virtual World from grave with its effects negated, sending a card from hand on resolution as well. 

Extra Deck: 1 Elder Entity N'tss which must be Special Summoned from your Extra Deck by sending a Synchro and an Xyz you control to the grave. On field, it can Special Summon a Level 4 from hand, not that you have any, but it is here to get Aggregator that has attached Herald into the grave. If you really wanted to, you could Synchro it with a Level 6 tuner into the 1 Baronne de Fleur that we are playing also. 1 Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen which is macro on legs for cards sent from field to grave. If you attack, you can return a banished monster to grave, and if it's in grave except during the turn it was sent there, you can banish 2 monsters with different types and attributes from grave to Summon it back. You don't really make this card unless you are able to at the end of your Prediction Princess combo to have monster on field that does something that interrupts your opponent. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which is a Synchro 9 that can draw a card for every non-Tuner used for its Synchro Summon and you can also Quick Effect discard 2 to pop a card on field. It is pretty much only a Level 9 that pluses you in drawing a card which is actually really good in a Deck like this. 1 Cloudcastle which Summons back a Level 9 from grave on Synchro Summon. Like you can detach a Level 9 from Aggregator to bring it back with Cloudcastle. It is just really good for extension and more plays. 1 Coral Dragon which allows you to discard a card to pop a card your opponent controls and it draws you a card if it's sent to grave after it has been Synchro Summoned. It is a plus in a draw when it's sent to grave and it is a Level 6 Tuner also. 1 Stardust Charge Warrior which draws a card on Synchro Summon which is simple but good. 1 Herald of the Arc Light for a Ritual search off of Aggregator. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck on Xyz Summon and can also detach any number of materials to attach the same number of mosnters from grave. 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity and 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows. You don't need to play them, but it is a good way to clear cards off the field and a good type of interruption. 1 Nine-Lives Cat which can detach 1 to Summon back a Level 9 from your grave or a monster from your opponent's grave. 1 Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal which can detach 1 to send any card from Deck to grave. If you need to, you can send Tarotrei or Tarotreith to get it into rotation as Underworld Ritual can Ritual from grave. 1 Number 49: Fortune Tune for Zeus shenanigans. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being. 2 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju. 1 Kurikara Divincarnate. 3 Dark Ruler No More. 3 Evenly Matched. 3 Solemn Strike.

I really like EARTH decks. There's just a thing about them for that works for me in terms of theme/options, and this has turned out to be pretty solid when playtesting. 

The general idea is that this deck is super flexable though multiple means, namely though Giant Rat targets. It bounces into whatever is needed essentially. These sort of bouncers are to be cleared though quickly and to bait removal targets before you then stomp around with Gigantes/Assailent to get in for damage. 

I wanted the same style as Warrior, so lots of proactive counters to popular plays, like Swordsman for flip, Attack Force for big targets, Tornado for backrow hate, etc.The real difference between this and Warrior decks is that we aren't restricted to merely those for this deck, meaning cards like Injection Fairy and Momonga get to have a shot. I'll definitely say that the Rat into Fairy combo has done gangbusters for the aggression of this deck by being able to go for mean early damage or using Fairy as a wrecker later in the game when points are more valued.

Swords Woman??? Weird choice for sure, but her respectable stats (alongside not really being effected by Book of Moon/Tsuk strats, which are typically popular for the bigger monsters you use) alongside being able to dish out fair damage if attacked over is always helpful. Momonga baits out Nobleman plays and can be really useful for either stalling out and/or milling the deck. 

2x Smashing Ground helps running over bigger targets that you don't want around. 3x Dustshoot is definitely debatable, but my own experience of using the deck, I've never had problems bricking or failing for targets. With Chaos Turbo throwing out Jars and stacking up on cards as it is, it's needed more than ever.

Side Deck plays with some concepts and counters. Mobius/Jinzo for backrow, Sangan to get plays out faster...Panda is a really solid alt-choice for Rat if you need to handle Scapegoat/facedown spam. Creature Swap/Last Will are popular choices for bouncer-themed decks, but they didn't really fit in the main proper. Everything else is just generic more or less.

deck_name: Plunder patroll PUNK with crystal beasts

deck_excerpt: Traptrix deck that km taking to locals/regional.

deck_description: A deck for the pharaoh Atem. roleplay deck

There are multiple ways to play this deck but the main goal here is to lock opponent's turn with Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity .

If you draw SHS engine then you can get free Adamancipator Risen - Raptite  and then continue with adamancipator engine.

1)Try and get a Superheavy Samurai Brave Masurawo  (Accel + lvl4 tuner or baronne with lvl 2 tuner) and then either pendulum summon the Flint Cragger  or special summon it with the adamancipator engine in order to get Fossil Fusion  by banishing the Fossil Dragon Skullgar . Make Cross-Sheep  and banish the accel + a rock monster into the fossil Convoy, activate cross-sheep to special summon lvl4 tuner Analyzer for GY and summon Crimson Dragon (card)  and draw the Trap card. Depending the board summon a Masquerena and End turn.

In opponent's turn with trap summon back Accel with the trap + crimson Dragon effect into the King Calamity by targeting Masurawo. So you have now in board Masurawo + King Calamity + Masquerena + Accel + probably another body(-> Apollousa). You prevent the opponent from activating a card so you OTK next round.

2) If you want to play safer or did not draw the Samurai engine you can end through negates into baronne + naturia beast + masquerena.

The remaining synchros are potential targets for Crimson dragon(lvl8 crystal wing - lvl10 stardust wing dragon)
